{"title_page": "Zsombor J\u00e9ger", "text_new": "{{eastern name order|J\u00e9ger Zsombor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = \n| image         =J\u00e9ger Zsombor.jpg  \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1991|03|16}}\n| birth_place   = [[Debrecen]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Hungarian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Actor\n| years_active  = 2016\u2013\n| known_for     = [[Jupiter's Moon]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Zsombor J\u00e9ger''' ({{IPA-hu|\u02c8\u0292ombor \u02c8je\u02d0\u0261\u025br|lang}}; born 16 March 1991) is a Hungarian actor. He had his debut age four in ''[[A dzsungel k\u00f6nyve]]'', a Hungarian musical based on ''[[The Jungle Book]]'', at the [[Csokonai Theatre]] in [[Debrecen]], where he later acted in several children and youth roles. J\u00e9ger is a graduate from the [[Academy of Drama and Film in Budapest]], and has been acting in several plays at the {{ill|\u00d6rk\u00e9ny Theatre|hu|\u00d6rk\u00e9ny Istv\u00e1n Sz\u00ednh\u00e1z|fr|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Istv\u00e1n \u00d6rk\u00e9ny}} in [[Erzs\u00e9betv\u00e1ros]], [[Budapest]].{{r|\"7\u00f3ra7\"}}\n\n==Early life and family background==\nZsombor J\u00e9ger was born in Debrecen Hungary. He is the son of J\u00e9ger Attila who is a piano tuner and has been playing in several bands in the mid 1990s playing alternative Blues. His mother Bandi Margit is a Hungarian teacher, and mental hygiene specialist. J\u00e9ger grew up with his two sisters who are also bonded with the Hungarian artistic sphere.\n\nAt an early age he started playing the violin and has been playing ever since. He plays many instruments in an autodidact way.\n\n== Films ==\n*[[Jupiter's Moon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"7\u00f3ra7\">{{cite web\n  | url        = http://7ora7.hu/2016/03/15/jeger_zsombor_en_nem_vagyok_szinesz\n  | title      = J\u00e9ger Zsombor: \"\u00c9n nem vagyok sz\u00edn\u00e9sz!\"\n  | work       = 7\u00f3ra7\n  | accessdate = 16 February 2017\n  | language   = hu\n  | first      = Szabo\n  | last       = Zsuzsa\n}}</ref>\n}}\n{{expand language|topic=|langcode=hu|otherarticle=J\u00e9ger Zsombor|date=February 2017}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jeger, Zsombor}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Hungarian male actors]]\n\n\n{{Hungary-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{eastern name order|J\u00e9ger Zsombor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = \n| image         =J\u00e9ger Zsombor.jpg  \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1991|03|16}}\n| birth_place   = [[Debrecen]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Hungarian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Actor\n| years_active  = 2016\u2013\n| known_for     = [[Jupiter's Moon]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Zsombor J\u00e9ger''' ({{IPA-hu|\u02c8\u0292ombor \u02c8je\u02d0\u0261\u025br|lang}}; born 16 March 1991) is a Hungarian actor. He had his debut age four in ''[[A dzsungel k\u00f6nyve]]'', a Hungarian musical based on ''[[The Jungle Book]]'', at the [[Csokonai Theatre]] in [[Debrecen]], where he later acted in several children and youth roles. J\u00e9ger is a graduate from the [[Academy of Drama and Film in Budapest]], and has been acting in several plays at the {{ill|\u00d6rk\u00e9ny Theatre|hu|\u00d6rk\u00e9ny Istv\u00e1n Sz\u00ednh\u00e1z|fr|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Istv\u00e1n \u00d6rk\u00e9ny}} in [[Erzs\u00e9betv\u00e1ros]], [[Budapest]].{{r|\"7\u00f3ra7\"}}\n\n==Early life and family background==\nZsombor J\u00e9ger was born in Debrecen Hungary. He is the son of J\u00e9ger Attila who is a piano tuner and has been playing in several bands in the mid 90's playing alternative Blues. His mother Bandi Margit is a Hungarian teacher, and mental hygiene specialist. J\u00e9ger grew up with his two sisters who are also bonded with the Hungarian artistic sphere.\n\nAt an early age he started playing the violin and has been playing ever since. He plays many instruments in an autodidact way.\n\n== Films ==\n*[[Jupiter's Moon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"7\u00f3ra7\">{{cite web\n  | url        = http://7ora7.hu/2016/03/15/jeger_zsombor_en_nem_vagyok_szinesz\n  | title      = J\u00e9ger Zsombor: \"\u00c9n nem vagyok sz\u00edn\u00e9sz!\"\n  | work       = 7\u00f3ra7\n  | accessdate = 16 February 2017\n  | language   = hu\n  | first      = Szabo\n  | last       = Zsuzsa\n}}</ref>\n}}\n{{expand language|topic=|langcode=hu|otherarticle=J\u00e9ger Zsombor|date=February 2017}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jeger, Zsombor}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Hungarian male actors]]\n\n\n{{Hungary-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zsombor_J%C3%A9ger"}
{"title_page": "Monaco/Government", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Politics_of_Monaco]]\n\n{{R from subpage}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Politics_of_Monaco]]\n", "name_user": "1234qwer1234qwer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:R from subpage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Monaco/Government&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Adam Fforde", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=December 2018}}\n{{notability|Academics|date=December 2018}}\n{{third-party|date=December 2018}}\n}}\n{{short description|economist}}\n'''Adam Fforde''' is an economist specializing in [[Vietnam]].\n\n==Education==\n\nBorn in London in 1953, he was educated at Westminster School and the [[University of Oxford]]. Changing his academic focus from Engineering to Economics, Fforde attained his Ph.D (with a thesis on 'Problems of Agricultural Development in North Vietnam') from [[Cambridge University]] in 1982.\n\n==Career==\n\nHe spent the 1980s and 1990s in Hanoi and Canberra advising on development practice for national aid agencies and NGOs operating in South-East Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vietnampolitics.net/?page_id=112|title=Adam Fforde CV July 2016 {{!}} vietnampolitics.net|website=vietnampolitics.net|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nAccepting a Fellowship in 1999 at the [[National University of Singapore]], Fforde subsequently held a number of academic posts in [[Melbourne, Australia]]. He is currently among the most widely cited academics writing on contemporary Vietnam,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://esacentral.org.au/business-listing/3767/0/240081/adam-fforde|title=Adam Fforde|website=esacentral.org.au|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> as well as the author of textbooks and critical works on the theory and methodology of development practice.\n\nHe is a Professorial Fellow at [[Victoria University, Australia|Victoria University's]] Centre for Strategic Economic Studies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vu.edu.au/contact-us/adam-fforde|title=Adam Fforde {{!}} Victoria University {{!}} Melbourne Australia|website=www.vu.edu.au|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nFforde is the eldest son of John Fforde (1921-2000), a senior figure in the Bank of England, and the brother of British novelist Jasper Fforde (born 1961).  He is married with four children and currently lives in Melbourne, Australia.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n* ''Reinventing \u2018development\u2019 \u2013 the sceptical change agent'', New York: Palgrave-MacMillan 2017. \n* ''Understanding development economics: its challenge to development studies'', 2013, London: Routledge\n* ''Coping with facts \u2013 a skeptic\u2019s guide to the problem of development,'' 2009, Bloomfield, CT: Kumarian Press.  \n* ''Vietnamese State Industry and the Political Economy of Commercial Renaissance: Dragon's tooth or curate's egg?'' 2007 Oxford: Chandos\n* ''The Agrarian Question in North Vietnam 1974-79: a study of cooperator resistance to State policy'', 1989, New York: M.E.Sharpe {{ISBN|0873324862}}\n* ''From Plan to Market: The Economic Transition in Vietnam'', Boulder CO: Westview, 1996. '''ASIN:''' 0813326834. (co-authored with Stefan de Vylder)\n* ''Vietnam - an economy in transition'', 1988, Stockholm: SIDA (ISBN n/a). (co-authored with Stefan de Vylder) \n* ''The Limits of National Liberation - problems of economic management in the Democratic Republic of Vietnam, with a Statistical Appendix'', 1987, London: Croom-Helm. {{ISBN|0709910363}}. (co-authored with S.H.Paine)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fforde, Adam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:English economists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Victoria University, Australia faculty]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Australia]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:21st-century economists]]\n[[Category:English economics writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=December 2018}}\n{{notability|Academics|date=December 2018}}\n{{third-party|date=December 2018}}\n}}\n{{short description|economist}}\n'''Adam Fforde''' is an economist specializing in [[Vietnam]].\n\n==Education==\n\nBorn in London in 1953, he was educated at Westminster School and the [[University of Oxford]]. Changing his academic focus from Engineering to Economics, Fforde attained his Ph.D (with a thesis on 'Problems of Agricultural Development in North Vietnam') from [[Cambridge University]] in 1982.\n\n==Career==\n\nHe spent the 1980s and 1990s in Hanoi and Canberra advising on development practice for national aid agencies and NGOs operating in South-East Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vietnampolitics.net/?page_id=112|title=Adam Fforde CV July 2016 {{!}} vietnampolitics.net|website=vietnampolitics.net|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nAccepting a Fellowship in 1999 at the [[National University of Singapore]], Fforde subsequently held a number of academic posts in [[Melbourne, Australia]]. He is currently among the most widely cited academics writing on contemporary Vietnam,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://esacentral.org.au/business-listing/3767/0/240081/adam-fforde|title=Adam Fforde|website=esacentral.org.au|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> as well as the author of textbooks and critical works on the theory and methodology of development practice.\n\nHe is a Professorial Fellow at [[Victoria University, Australia|Victoria University's]] Centre for Strategic Economic Studies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vu.edu.au/contact-us/adam-fforde|title=Adam Fforde {{!}} Victoria University {{!}} Melbourne Australia|website=www.vu.edu.au|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nFforde is the eldest son of John Fforde (1921-2000), a senior figure in the Bank of England, and the brother of British novelist Jasper Fforde (born 1961).  He is married with four children and currently lives in Melbourne, Australia.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n* ''Reinventing \u2018development\u2019 \u2013 the sceptical change agent'', New York: Palgrave-MacMillan 2017. \n* ''Understanding development economics: its challenge to development studies'', 2013, London: Routledge\n* ''Coping with facts \u2013 a skeptic\u2019s guide to the problem of development,'' 2009, Bloomfield, CT: Kumarian Press.  \n* ''Vietnamese State Industry and the Political Economy of Commercial Renaissance: Dragon's tooth or curate's egg?'' 2007 Oxford: Chandos\n* ''The Agrarian Question in North Vietnam 1974-79: a study of cooperator resistance to State policy'', 1989, New York: M.E.Sharpe {{ISBN|0873324862}}\n* ''From Plan to Market: The Economic Transition in Vietnam'', Boulder CO: Westview, 1996. '''ASIN:''' 0813326834. (co-authored with Stefan de Vylder)\n* ''Vietnam - an economy in transition'', 1988, Stockholm: SIDA (ISBN n/a). (co-authored with Stefan de Vylder) \n* ''The Limits of National Liberation - problems of economic management in the Democratic Republic of Vietnam, with a Statistical Appendix'', 1987, London: Croom-Helm. {{ISBN|0709910363}}. (co-authored with S.H.Paine)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fforde, Adam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:English economists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Victoria University, Australia faculty]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Australia]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:21st-century economists]]\n[[Category:English economics writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam_Fforde"}
{"title_page": "Matheus Machado", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Matheus Machado\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2001|7|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]]\n| height = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]]\n| clubnumber = 27\n| youthyears1 = \u20132018\n| youthclubs1 = [[Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras|Palmeiras]]\n| youthyears2 = 2018\n| youthclubs2 = [[Red Bull Brasil]]\n| years1 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]]\n| caps1 = 1\n| goals1 = 0\n| club-update = 14:53, 1 December 2019 (UTC)\n| youthclubs3 = [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]]\n| youthyears3 = 2018\u20132019\n}}\n'''Matheus Machado''' (born 9 July 2001) is a Brazilian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays for Scottish club [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]], as a [[midfielder]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ictfc.com/player/matheus-machado|title=Matheus Machado}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMachado began his career with [[Red Bull Brasil]], signing for Scottish club [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45289943|title=Inverness sign Brazilian teenager from Red Bull in Sao Paulo|date=23 August 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> He was included in a first-team squad for the first time in March 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ictfc.com/matheus-machado-in-squad-for-partick-thistle-game|title=Matheus Machado in squad for Partick Thistle game|date=21 March 2019}}</ref> and made his debut in the 2019\u201320 season, coming on late in a 3-1 loss to [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>{{soccerbase season|119481|2019|accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Machado, Matheus}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Red Bull Brasil players]]\n[[Category:Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n\n{{Brazil-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Matheus Machado\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2001|7|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]]\n| height = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]]\n| clubnumber = 27\n| youthyears1 = \u20132018\n| youthclubs1 = [[Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras|Palmeiras]]\n| youthyears2 = 2018\n| youthclubs2 = [[Red Bull Brasil]]\n| years1 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]]\n| caps1 = 1\n| goals1 = 0\n| club-update = 14:53, 1 December 2019 (UTC)\n| youthclubs3 = [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]]\n| youthyears3 = 2018\u20132019\n}}\n'''Matheus Machado''' (born 9 July 2001) is a Brazilian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays for Scottish club [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]], as a [[midfielder]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ictfc.com/player/matheus-machado|title=Matheus Machado}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMachado began his career with [[Red Bull Brasil]], signing for Scottish club [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45289943|title=Inverness sign Brazilian teenager from Red Bull in Sao Paulo|date=23 August 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> He was included in a first-team squad for the first time in March 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ictfc.com/matheus-machado-in-squad-for-partick-thistle-game|title=Matheus Machado in squad for Partick Thistle game|date=21 March 2019}}</ref> and made his debut in the 2019\u201320 season.<ref>{{soccerbase season|119481|2019|accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Machado, Matheus}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Red Bull Brasil players]]\n[[Category:Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n\n{{Brazil-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cheesy McGee", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matheus_Machado"}
{"title_page": "Memorial Day Pensacola Beach Pride", "text_new": "{{COI|date=September 2015}}\n'''Gay Memorial Day Weekend''' in Pensacola is an annual beach gathering of thousands of [[LGBT]] locals and tourists during the [[Memorial Day]] holiday weekend.<ref>[http://www.tampabay.com/news/courts/gay-couples-travel-from-neighboring-counties-and-states-to-wed-in-pensacola/2212682 \"Gay couples travel from neighboring counties, states to wed in Pensacola\"] ''Tampa Bay Times''. Retrieved 2015-4-16.</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe summer event has roots back to the 1960s.\n\n===Emma Jones Society on Independence Day===\nA local gay couple invited a group of gay friends to the beach for Independence Day. Until the mid-1970s the gathering was held during Fourth of July weekend. This group, also known as the Emma Jones Society, hosted this gather during the inaugural years, which during the late 1960s and early 1970s was held at the [[San Carlos Hotel (Pensacola, Florida)|San Carlos Hotel]] (since demolished) in downtown Pensacola. Events there included impersonations, skits, drag queen performances, and a male beauty pageant, Mr. U.S. Gay. These parties ended in 1975.<ref>[http://inweekly.net/wordpress/?p=15308 \"Queer and Here: The Long History of Gay Tourists on Pensacola Beach\"] ''IN Weekly''. Retrieved 2015-4-16.</ref>\n\n===Rebirth on Memorial Day===\nThe idea of a summer gather rejuvenated in the early 80s being focused at the beginning of the summer during Memorial Day weekend. In the late-1980s, Atlanta's Steve Berman began to host circuit parties and the event continued to grow. In the mid-1990s, New Orleans bar-owner Johnny Chisholm took over events after purchasing the non-defunct LGBT bar Emerald City.\n\n===Disasters of the 2000s===\nThe weekend celebration was at a peak until [[Hurricane Ivan]] hit during 2004, followed just months later by [[Hurricane Dennis]]. Area recovery from these severe weather disasters dampened the event for a few years. The BP oil spill also affected the event's growth and offerings following that 2010 disaster in the [[Gulf of Mexico]].\n\n==Events==\nMemorial Day Weekend in Pensacola consists of two types of activities.\n\nThe most promoted, for obvious commercial reasons, are the circuit parties. They are hosted and run by local and traveling companies who set up large, elaborate sound systems, light shows, and hire well-known professional [[DJ]]'s. Tickets to the mainly alcohol-free events can be over $75 with discounts available for multiple party tickets. The parties often start late, some at 11:00pm and do not end until shortly before sunrise.\n\nThe second type of activity, though probably more heavily attended than the [[circuit parties]], is simply sitting on the beach. There are literally thousands of large shade tents and dozens that are elaborately outfitted with themed decors, full wet bars, and hand-dug [[jacuzzi]]s. Most of this crowd begins to arrive around 6:45am in time to see the last circuit party-goer leaving.\n\n==Pensacola Women's Week==\nFor the women, there's Pensacola Women's Week. The women's events include beach [[dodgeball]], a comedy show, a highly coveted drag king competition, international superstar performances and a seductive pool party at the Holiday Inn Resort. These events take place on the beach, as well, at the Captain Fun's bar.\n\n==Criticism and response==\nThe event, especially since its popularity grew, has been denounced by local religious leaders and groups for decades including on-site protesters at several of the event venues around the area.\n\nIn 1993, City of Pensacola officials spoke out about not wanting to be associated with or known as being a \"gay-friendly\" destination. Yet, the positive economic impact on the area has hushed most of the disdain of local conservatives.<ref>[http://inweekly.net/wordpress/?p=15314 \"Gay Money: The Uncertain Economics of Memorial Day Weekend on the Beach\"] ''IN Weekly''. Retrieved 2015-4-16.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Pensacola metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:LGBT events in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=September 2015}}\n'''Gay Memorial Day Weekend''' in Pensacola is an annual beach gathering of thousands of [[LGBT]] locals and tourists during the [[Memorial Day]] holiday weekend.<ref>[http://www.tampabay.com/news/courts/gay-couples-travel-from-neighboring-counties-and-states-to-wed-in-pensacola/2212682 \"Gay couples travel from neighboring counties, states to wed in Pensacola\"] ''Tampa Bay Times''. Retrieved 2015-4-16.</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe summer event has roots back to the 1960s.\n\n===Emma Jones Society on Independence Day===\nA local gay couple invited a group of gay friends to the beach for Independence Day. Until the mid-70's the gathering was held during Fourth of July weekend. This group, also known as the Emma Jones Society, hosted this gather during the inaugural years, which during the late 60's and early 70's was held at the [[San Carlos Hotel (Pensacola, Florida)|San Carlos Hotel]] (since demolished) in downtown Pensacola. Events there included impersonations, skits, drag queen performances, and a male beauty pageant, Mr. U.S. Gay. These parties ended in 1975.<ref>[http://inweekly.net/wordpress/?p=15308 \"Queer and Here: The Long History of Gay Tourists on Pensacola Beach\"] ''IN Weekly''. Retrieved 2015-4-16.</ref>\n\n===Rebirth on Memorial Day===\nThe idea of a summer gather rejuvenated in the early 80s being focused at the beginning of the summer during Memorial Day weekend. In the late-80's, Atlanta's Steve Berman began to host circuit parties and the event continued to grow. In the mid-90's, New Orleans bar-owner Johnny Chisholm took over events after purchasing the non-defunct LGBT bar Emerald City.\n\n===Disasters of the 2000s===\nThe weekend celebration was at a peak until [[Hurricane Ivan]] hit during 2004, followed just months later by [[Hurricane Dennis]]. Area recovery from these severe weather disasters dampened the event for a few years. The BP oil spill also affected the event's growth and offerings following that 2010 disaster in the [[Gulf of Mexico]].\n\n==Events==\nMemorial Day Weekend in Pensacola consists of two types of activities.\n\nThe most promoted, for obvious commercial reasons, are the circuit parties. They are hosted and run by local and traveling companies who set up large, elaborate sound systems, light shows, and hire well-known professional [[DJ]]'s. Tickets to the mainly alcohol-free events can be over $75 with discounts available for multiple party tickets. The parties often start late, some at 11:00pm and do not end until shortly before sunrise.\n\nThe second type of activity, though probably more heavily attended than the [[circuit parties]], is simply sitting on the beach. There are literally thousands of large shade tents and dozens that are elaborately outfitted with themed decors, full wet bars, and hand-dug [[jacuzzi]]s. Most of this crowd begins to arrive around 6:45am in time to see the last circuit party-goer leaving.\n\n==Pensacola Women's Week==\nFor the women, there's Pensacola Women's Week. The women's events include beach [[dodgeball]], a comedy show, a highly coveted drag king competition, international superstar performances and a seductive pool party at the Holiday Inn Resort. These events take place on the beach, as well, at the Captain Fun's bar.\n\n==Criticism and response==\nThe event, especially since its popularity grew, has been denounced by local religious leaders and groups for decades including on-site protesters at several of the event venues around the area.\n\nIn 1993, City of Pensacola officials spoke out about not wanting to be associated with or known as being a \"gay-friendly\" destination. Yet, the positive economic impact on the area has hushed most of the disdain of local conservatives.<ref>[http://inweekly.net/wordpress/?p=15314 \"Gay Money: The Uncertain Economics of Memorial Day Weekend on the Beach\"] ''IN Weekly''. Retrieved 2015-4-16.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Pensacola metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:LGBT events in Florida]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memorial_Day_Pensacola_Beach_Pride"}
{"title_page": "April 10", "text_new": "{{About|the day of the year|the song by Garbage|April Tenth}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n* [[428]] &ndash; [[Nestorius]] becomes the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople|Patriarch of Constantinople]].\n* [[837]] &ndash; [[Halley's Comet]] makes its closest approach to Earth at a distance equal to 0.0342 [[Astronomical unit|AU]] (5.1 million kilometres/3.2 million miles).\n*[[1407]] &ndash; [[Deshin Shekpa, 5th Karmapa Lama]] visits the [[Ming dynasty]] capital at [[Nanjing]]. He is awarded the title \"Great Treasure Prince of Dharma\".\n*[[1500]] &ndash; [[Ludovico Sforza]] is captured by Swiss troops at [[Novara]] and is handed over to the French.\n*[[1606]] &ndash; The [[London Company|Virginia Company of London]] is established by royal charter by [[James I of England]] with the purpose of establishing [[British colonization of the Americas|colonial settlements in North America]].\n*[[1710]] &ndash; The [[Statute of Anne]], the first law regulating [[copyright]], comes into force in [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]].\n*[[1741]] &ndash; [[War of the Austrian Succession]]: Prussia gains control of [[Silesia]] at the [[Battle of Mollwitz]].\n*[[1809]] &ndash; [[Napoleonic Wars]]: The [[War of the Fifth Coalition]] begins when forces of the [[Austrian Empire]] invade [[Bavaria]].\n*[[1815]] &ndash; The [[Mount Tambora]] volcano begins a three-month-long eruption, lasting until [[July 15]]. The eruption ultimately kills 71,000 people and [[Year Without a Summer|affects Earth's climate]] for the next two years.\n*[[1816]] &ndash; The [[Federal government of the United States]] approves the creation of the [[Second Bank of the United States]].\n*[[1821]] &ndash; Patriarch [[Gregory V of Constantinople]] is hanged by the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman government]] from the main gate of the [[Patriarchate]] and his body is thrown into the [[Bosphorus]].\n*[[1826]] &ndash; The 10,500 inhabitants of the Greek town of [[Missolonghi]] begin leaving the town after [[Third Siege of Missolonghi|a year's siege]] by Turkish forces. Very few of them survive.\n*[[1858]] &ndash; After the original [[Big Ben]], a {{Convert|14.5|tonne|lb}} bell for the [[Palace of Westminster]], had cracked during testing, it is recast into the current {{convert|13.76|tonne|lb}} bell by [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]].\n*[[1864]] &ndash; Archduke [[Maximilian I of Mexico|Maximilian of Habsburg]] is proclaimed emperor of Mexico during the [[French intervention in Mexico]].\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: A day after his surrender to Union forces, Confederate General Robert E. Lee [[Lee's Farewell Address|addresses]] his troops for the last time.\n*[[1866]] &ndash; The [[American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals]] (ASPCA) is founded in New York City by [[Henry Bergh]].\n*[[1868]] &ndash; At Arogee in [[Ethiopia|Abyssinia]], British and Indian forces [[British Expedition to Abyssinia|defeat]] an army of Emperor [[Tewodros II]]. While 700 [[Ethiopia]]ns are killed and many more injured, only two British/Indian troops die.\n*[[1872]] &ndash; The first [[Arbor Day]] is celebrated in [[Nebraska]].\n*[[1887]] &ndash; On [[Easter Sunday]], [[Pope Leo XIII]] authorizes the establishment of the [[Catholic University of America]].\n*[[1912]] &ndash; ''[[RMS Titanic]]'' sets sail from [[Southampton]], England on her maiden and only voyage.\n*[[1916]] &ndash; The [[Professional Golfers' Association of America]] (PGA) is created in New York City.\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[Mexican Revolution]] leader [[Emiliano Zapata]] is ambushed and shot dead by government forces in [[Morelos]].\n*[[1925]] &ndash; ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'' by [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]] is first published in New York City, by [[Charles Scribner's Sons]].\n*[[1938]] &ndash; [[1938 German parliamentary election and referendum]], the final elections to the Reichstag during Nazi rule and seeking approval for the recent [[annexation of Austria]]\n*[[1939]] &ndash; ''[[Alcoholics Anonymous]]'', A.A.'s \"Big Book\" is first published.\n*[[1941]] &ndash; World War II: The [[Axis powers]] establish the [[Independent State of Croatia]].\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[Rudolf Vrba]] and [[Alfr\u00e9d Wetzler]] escape from [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Birkenau death camp]].\n*[[1957]] &ndash; The [[Suez Canal]] is reopened for all shipping after being closed for three months.\n*[[1963]] &ndash; One hundred twenty-nine American sailors die when the [[submarine]] {{USS|Thresher|SSN-593|6}} sinks at sea.\n*[[1968]] &ndash; The [[TEV Wahine|TEV ''Wahine'']], a New Zealand ferry sinks in Wellington harbour due to a fierce storm - the strongest winds ever in Wellington. Out of the 734 people on board, fifty-three died.\n*[[1970]] &ndash; [[Paul McCartney]] announces that he is leaving [[The Beatles]] for personal and professional reasons.\n*[[1971]] &ndash; [[Ping-pong diplomacy]]: In an attempt to thaw relations with the United States, China hosts the U.S. [[table tennis]] team for a week-long visit.\n*[[1972]] &ndash; [[Yinqueshan Han Tombs|Tombs]] containing [[Yinqueshan Han Slips|bamboo slips]], among them [[Sun Tzu]]'s ''[[The Art of War|Art of War]]'' and [[Sun Bin]]'s lost [[Sun Bin's Art of War|military treatise]], are accidentally discovered by construction workers in [[Shandong]].\n*  1972   &ndash; [[Vietnam War]]: For the first time since November [[1967]], American [[B-52 Stratofortress|B-52 bombers]] reportedly begin bombing [[North Vietnam]].\n*[[1973]] &ndash; [[Invicta International Airlines Flight 435]] crashes in a snowstorm on approach to [[Basel]], Switzerland killing 108 people.\n*[[1979]] &ndash; [[1979 Red River Valley tornado outbreak|Red River Valley tornado outbreak]]: A tornado lands in [[Wichita Falls, Texas]] killing 42 people.\n*[[1988]] &ndash; The [[Ojhri Camp]] explosion kills or injures more than 1,000 people in [[Rawalpindi]] and [[Islamabad]].\n*[[1991]] &ndash; Italian ferry {{ship|MS|Moby Prince||6}} collides with an oil tanker in dense fog off [[Livorno]], Italy killing 140.\n*  1991   &ndash; A [[South Atlantic tropical cyclone|rare]] [[tropical cyclone|tropical storm]] develops in the South [[Atlantic Ocean]] near [[Angola]]; the first to be documented by [[weather satellite|satellites]].\n*[[1998]] &ndash; The [[Good Friday Agreement]] is signed in Northern Ireland.\n*[[2009]] &ndash; [[President of Fiji]] [[Ratu]] [[Josefa Iloilo]] announces the abrogation of the [[1997 Constitution of Fiji|constitution]] and assumes all governance in the country, creating a [[2009 Fijian constitutional crisis|constitutional crisis]].\n*[[2010]] &ndash; [[Polish Air Force]] Tu-154M [[2010 Polish Air Force Tu-154 crash|crashes]] near [[Smolensk]], [[Russia]], killing 96 people, including Polish President [[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski]], his wife, and dozens of other senior officials and dignitaries.\n*[[2016]] &ndash; The [[Paravur temple accident]] in which a devastating fire caused by the explosion of firecrackers stored for [[Vishu]], kills more than one hundred people out of the thousands gathered for seventh day of [[Bhadrakali]] worship.\n*  2016   &ndash; An [[2016 Afghanistan earthquake|earthquake]], of 6.6 magnitude, strikes 39&nbsp;km west-southwest of [[Ashkasham]], shakes up India, Afghanistan, Tajikistan, Srinagar and Pakistan.\n*[[2019]] &ndash; Scientists from the [[Event Horizon Telescope]] project announce the first ever image of a [[black hole]], located in the centre of the [[Messier 87|M87]] galaxy\n\n==Births==\n<!-- Please do not add yourself or anyone else without a biography in Wikipedia to this list.-->\n* [[401]] &ndash; [[Theodosius II]], Roman emperor (d. 450)\n*[[1018]] &ndash; [[Nizam al-Mulk]],  Persian scholar and vizier (d. 1092)\n*[[1472]] &ndash; [[Margaret of York (1472)|Margaret of York]], English princess (d. 1472)\n*[[1480]] &ndash; [[Philibert II, Duke of Savoy|Philibert II]], duke of Savoy (d. 1504)\n*[[1487]] &ndash; [[William I, Count of Nassau-Dillenburg|William I]], count of Nassau-Dillenburg (d. 1559)\n*[[1512]] &ndash; [[James V of Scotland|James V]], king of Scotland (d. 1542)\n*[[1579]] &ndash; [[Augustus the Younger, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Augustus II]], duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg (d. 1666)\n*[[1583]] &ndash; [[Hugo Grotius]], Dutch philosopher and jurist (d. 1645)\n*[[1603]] &ndash; [[Christian, Prince-Elect of Denmark|Christian]], Prince-Elect of Denmark (d. 1647)\n*[[1651]] &ndash; [[Ehrenfried Walther von Tschirnhaus]], German mathematician, physicist, and physician (d. 1708)\n*[[1656]] &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9 Lepage de Sainte-Claire]], French-Canadian settler, founded [[Rimouski]] (d. 1718)\n*[[1704]] &ndash; [[Benjamin Heath]], English scholar and author (d. 1766)\n*[[1707]] &ndash; [[Michel Corrette]], French organist, composer, and author (d. 1795)\n*[[1713]] &ndash; [[John Whitehurst]], English geologist and clockmaker (d. 1788)\n*[[1755]] &ndash; [[Samuel Hahnemann]], German-French physician and academic (d. 1843)\n*[[1762]] &ndash; [[Giovanni Aldini]], Italian physicist and academic (d. 1834)\n*[[1769]] &ndash; [[Jean Lannes]], French marshal (d. 1809)\n*[[1778]] &ndash; [[William Hazlitt]], English essayist and critic (d. 1830)\n*[[1794]] &ndash; [[Matthew C. Perry]], English-Scottish American commander (d. 1858)\n*[[1806]] &ndash; [[Juliette Drouet]], French actress (d. 1883)\n*  1806   &ndash; [[Leonidas Polk]], Scottish-American general and bishop (d. 1884)\n*[[1827]] &ndash; [[Lew Wallace]], American general, lawyer, and politician, 11th [[Governor of New Mexico Territory]] (d. 1905)\n*[[1829]] &ndash; [[William Booth]], English minister, founded [[The Salvation Army]] (d. 1912)\n*[[1847]] &ndash; [[Joseph Pulitzer]], Hungarian-American journalist, publisher, and politician, founded [[Pulitzer, Inc.]] (d. 1911)\n*[[1864]] &ndash; [[Eugen d'Albert]], Scottish-German pianist and composer (d. 1932