ate=30 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925104735/http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=APAB&d_place=APAB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10B6E71B0D229838&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|archive-date=25 September 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*  [[Robert Heffernan]] finished fourth in the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 50 kilometres walk|2012 men's 50 kilometres walk]] won by [[Sergey Kirdyapkin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olympic.org/olympic-results/london-2012/athletics/50km-walk-m |title=50km walk men results \u2013 Athletics \u2013 London 2012 Olympics}}</ref> On 24 March 2016, the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]] disqualified all Kirdyapkin's competitive results from 20 August 2009 to 15 October 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tas-cas.org/fileadmin/user_upload/Media_Release_announce_decision.pdf |title=The Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS) Upholds Six Appeals Filed by the IAAF Against Russian Athlete. |format=PDF}}</ref> Hefferan was upgraded to third, and formally presented with a bronze medal in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/irish-race-walker-heffernan-to-receive-london-2012-medal-over-russian-doping-34569782.html|title=Irish race walker Heffernan to receive London 2012 medal over Russian doping|author=[[Press Association]]|date=24 March 2016|work=[[Irish Independent]]|quote=The IAAF will begin the process of reallocating two World Championship gold medals as well as Olympic medals following the CAS verdict. The IOC will formally redistribute the Olympic medals.|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/video/sport/rob-heffernan-finally-receives-his-just-reward--an-olympic-medal-428998.html|title=Rob Heffernan finally receives his just reward - an Olympic medal|last=Cormican|first=Eoghan|date=4 November 2016|work=Irish Examiner|accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Medallists in art competitions ===\n{{main|List of Olympic medallists in art competitions}}\n[[Art competitions at the Summer Olympics|Art competitions]] were held from [[Art competitions at the 1912 Summer Olympics|1912]] to [[Art competitions at the 1948 Summer Olympics|1948]]. Irish entries first appeared in [[Art competitions at the 1924 Summer Olympics|1924]], when they won two medals; a third was won in the 1948 competition.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:5em\"| Medal\n! style=\"width:13em\"| Name\n! style=\"width:10em\"| Games\n! style=\"width:10em\"| Event\n! style=\"width:30em\"| Piece\n|-\n| {{silver medal}} || {{sortname|Jack Butler|Yeats}} || {{GamesName|SOG|1924}} || Mixed Painting || ''Natation''<ref name=\"rep1924\"/> (\"Swimming\"; now on display in the [[National Gallery of Ireland]] with the title ''The [[River Liffey|Liffey]] Swim''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalgallery.ie/Collection/Selected%20Highlights/Yeats%20Collection/The%20Liffey%20Swim.aspx|title=The Liffey Swim|publisher=National Gallery of Ireland|accessdate=30 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031053303/http://www.nationalgallery.ie/Collection/Selected%20Highlights/Yeats%20Collection/The%20Liffey%20Swim.aspx|archivedate=31 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>)\n|-\n| {{bronze medal}} || {{sortname|Oliver|St. John Gogarty}} || {{GamesName|SOG|1924}} || Mixed Literature || ''Ode pour les Jeux de Tailteann''<ref name=\"rep1924\">{{cite journal|title = Les Jeux de la VIIIE Olympiade|pages = 605\u2013612|publisher = [[French Olympic Committee|Comite Olympique Francais]]|location = [[Paris]]|year = 1924|language = French}}</ref> (''Tailteann Ode'', which had won the prize for poetry at the revived [[Tailteann Games (Irish Free State)|Tailteann Games]] earlier that year<ref name=\"Cronin2003\">{{cite journal|last=Cronin|first=Mike|year=2003|title=Projecting the Nation through Sport and Culture: Ireland, Aonach Tailteann and the Irish Free State, 1924-32|journal=Journal of Contemporary History|volume=38|issue=3|pages=395\u2013411|issn=1461-7250|doi=10.1177/0022009403038003004|url=http://jch.sagepub.com/content/38/3/395.short}}</ref>)  Gogarty was awarded a bronze medal despite two silver medals being awarded in the category.<ref>MacCarthy 2010, p.391,fn.29</ref>\n|-\n| {{bronze medal}} || {{sortname|Letitia Marion|Hamilton}} || {{GamesName|SOG|1948}} || Paintings || ''Meath Hunt [[Point to point (steeplechase)|Point-to-Point Races]]''<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Official Report of the Organising Committee for the XIV Olympiad London 1948 |pages=535\u2013537 |publisher=The Organising Committee for the XIV Olympiad |location=[[London]] |year=1951 |url=http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1948/OR1948.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2012-03-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716035822/http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1948/OR1948.pdf |archivedate=16 July 2011 }}</ref> (a painting in 2012 \"believed to be somewhere in the United States\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2012/0309/olympics_ireland.html|title=1948 Irish Olympians honoured|date=9 March 2012|work=[[RT\u00c9.ie]]|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>)\n|}\n\n==Before independence==\n{{see also|List of Olympic competitors from Ireland who represented other countries}}\nPrior to 1922, Ireland was part of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]. Competitors at earlier Games born and living in Ireland are thus counted as British in Olympic statistics. At early Olympics, [[Irish American|Irish-born]] athletes won numerous medals for the [[United States at the Olympics|United States]], notably the \"[[Irish Whales]]\" in [[throwing event]]s.\n\nThe Irish Amateur Athletic Association was invited to the inaugural [[International Olympic Committee]] meeting in 1894, and may have been invited to the 1896 games; it has also been claimed the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] was invited.<ref name=\"MacCarthy 16\">MacCarthy 2010, pp.16\u201321</ref> In the event, neither participated.<ref name=\"MacCarthy 16\" />  Prior to the [[1906 Intercalated Games]], [[National Olympic Committee]]s (NOCs) were generally non-existent and athletes could enter the Olympics individually. [[John Pius Boland]], who came first in two tennis events in 1896, is now listed as \"IRL/GBR\";<ref name=\"ocihistory\"/><ref>[https://archive.is/20120907035507/http://www.olympic.org/en/Multimedia-Player/All-Photos/1896/01/01/RAAEE042/?CurrentMediaPageIPP=20&CurrentMediaPage=4&SortOrder=rate Athens 1896-BOLAND John Pius (IRL/GBR)] Olympic.org</ref>  Boland's daughter later claimed that he had objected when the Union Jack was raised to mark his triumph, and that the organisers apologised for not having an Irish flag.<ref name=\"MacCarthy30\" /> Kevin MacCarthy is sceptical of this story, though by 1906 Boland was crediting his medals to \"Ireland\".<ref name=\"MacCarthy30\">MacCarthy 2010, pp.30\u201337</ref> \n\n[[Tom Kiely]], who won [[Athletics at the 1904 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's decathlon|the \"all-around\" athletics competition]] at the [[1904 Summer Olympics|1904 Olympics in St Louis]] is also listed as competing for \"Great Britain\". <ref>[http://www.olympic.org/en/content/All-Olympic-results-since-1896/?AthleteName=Enter%20a%20name&Category=343488&Games=1333722&Sport=1313725&Event=&MenGender=true&WomenGender=false&MixedGender=false&TeamClassification=false&IndividualClassification=true&Continent=1310290&Country=&GoldMedal=true&SilverMedal=false&BronzeMedal=false&WorldRecord=false&OlympicRecord=false&TargetResults=true Thomas Francis Kiely, Great Britain] Olympic.org</ref> He had raised funds in counties [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]] and [[County Waterford|Waterford]] to travel independently and compete for Ireland.<ref name=\"sullivan\">{{cite journal |last=O'Sullivan |first=Patrick T.  |date=Spring 1998 |title=Ireland & the Olympic Games |journal=History Ireland |location=Dublin |volume=6 |issue=1 |url=http://www.historyireland.com/volumes/volume6/issue1/features/?id=180 }}</ref> [[Frank Zarnowski]] does not regard the 1904 event as part of the Olympic competition, and doubts the story that Kiely had refused offers by both the English [[Amateur Athletic Association]] (AAA) and the [[New York Athletic Club]] to pay his fare so he could compete for them.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/><ref name=\"Zarnowski2005\">{{cite book|last=Zarnowski|first=Frank|title=All-around Men: Heroes of a Forgotten Sport|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eXOBPt_Gi44C&pg=PA113|accessdate=12 April 2016|year=2005|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810854239|pages=113\u2013125: 118|chapter=Thomas F. Kiely}}</ref> Peter Lovesey disagrees with Zarnowski.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lovesey|first=Peter|date=November 2007|title=Letter to the editor|journal=Journal of Olympic History|publisher=[[International Society of Olympic Historians]]|volume=15|issue=3|pages=84\u20135|url=http://library.la84.org/SportsLibrary/JOH/JOHv15n3/JOHv15n3x.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe [[British Olympic Association]] (BOA) was formed in 1905, and Irish athletes were accredited to the BOA team from the 1906 Games onwards. Whereas [[Pierre de Coubertin]] recognised teams from [[Bohemia at the 1906 Intercalated Games|Bohemia]] and [[Finland at the 1906 Intercalated Games|Finland]] separately from their respective imperial powers, [[Austria at the 1906 Intercalated Games|Austria]] and [[Russian Empire at the 1908 Summer Olympics|Russia]], he was unwilling to make a similar distinction for Ireland, either because it lacked a [[National Olympic Committee]], or for fear of offending Britain.<ref>{{cite conference |url=http://library.la84.org/SportsLibrary/ISOR/isor2010l.pdf |title=A \u2018United\u2019 Kingdom? Nationalism, Identity and the Modern Olympic Games |first=Matthew |last=Llewellyn |year=2010 |conference=Tenth International Symposium for Olympic Research |book-title=Rethinking Matters Olympic: Investigations into the Socio-Cultural Study of the Modern Olympic Movement |publisher=International Centre for Olympic Studies |location=University of Western Ontario London, Ontario, Canada |format=PDF |id= |isbn= |access-date=23 October 2015 |pages=94\u2013105 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304122102/http://library.la84.org/SportsLibrary/ISOR/isor2010l.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At the 1906 Games, [[Peter O'Connor (athlete)|Peter O'Connor]] and [[Con Leahy]]  objected when the British flag was raised at their victory ceremony, and raised a green Irish flag in defiance of the organisers.<ref name=\"ocihistory\">[http://www.olympicsport.ie/about/3022-oci-history.html OCI History], Olympic Council of Ireland</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=15 February 2008 |title=''This Flag Dips for No Earthly King': The Mysterious Origins of an American Myth'|journal=International Journal of the History of Sport|publisher=Routledge|volume=25 |issue=2 |pages=142\u2013162 |doi=10.1080/09523360701740299}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1908 Summer Olympics|1908 Games]] in [[London]], there were multiple BOA entries in several team events, including two representing Ireland. In [[Field hockey at the 1908 Summer Olympics|the hockey tournament]], [[Ireland men's national field hockey team|the Irish team]] finished second, behind [[England men's national field hockey team|England]] and ahead of [[Scotland men's national field hockey team|Scotland]] and  [[Wales national field hockey team|Wales]].  The Irish [[polo]] team finished joint second in [[Polo at the 1908 Summer Olympics|the three-team tournament]], despite losing to one of two English teams in its only match.\n\nAt the 1912 Olympics, and despite objections from other countries, the BOA entered three teams in [[Cycling at the 1912 Summer Olympics|the cycling events]], one from each of the separate English, Scottish and Irish governing bodies for the sport.<ref name=\"MacCarthy253\">MacCarthy 2010, pp.242,253\u20138</ref> The Irish team came 11th in [[Cycling at the 1912 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team time trial|the team time trial]].<ref name=\"MacCarthy253\"/> The organisers had proposed a similar division in the [[Football at the 1912 Summer Olympics|football tournament]], but the BOA demurred.<ref name=\"MacCarthy242\">MacCarthy 2010, p.242</ref>\n\nA 1913 list of 35 countries to be invited to the [[1916 Olympics]] included Ireland separately from Great Britain; similarly Finland and Hungary were to be separate from Russia and Austria, although Bohemia was not listed.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kol\u00e1r|first=Franti\u0161ek|first2=Jir\u00ed |last2=K\u00f6ssl|date=Winter 1996|title=Pierre De Coubertin and the Czech Lands|journal=Citius Altius Fortius|publisher=International Society of Olympic Historians|location=Durham, NC, USA|volume=4|issue=1|pages=5\u201316: 11, fn.37|url=http://library.la84.org/SportsLibrary/JOH/JOHv4n1/JOHv4n1e.pdf#page=7|format=PDF|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> A newspaper report of the 1914 Olympic Congress says it endorsed a controversial [[German Olympic Committee]] proposal that \"now\u2014contrary to the hitherto existing practice\u2014only political nations may participate as teams in the Olympic Games\", with the \"United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland\" among these \"political nations\".<ref>{{cite conference |url=http://library.la84.org/SportsLibrary/ISOR/isor2010p.pdf#page=7  |title=The Olympic Games and Politics, 1896\u20131916 |first=Karl  |last=Lennartz |year=2010 |conference=10th International Symposium for Olympic Research |editor-first1=R.K. |editor-last1=Barney  |editor-first2=J. |editor-last2=Forsyth  |editor-first3=M.K. |editor-last3=Heine  |book-title=Rethinking Matters Olympic: Investigations into the Socio-Cultural Study of the Modern Olympic Movement  |publisher=ICOS |location=London, Ontario |format=PDF  |isbn=0-7714-2518-X |access-date=15 September 2017 |pages=138\u2013145 : 144  }}\n\n</ref> In the event, the games were cancelled due to the [[First World War]]. \n\nAfter the war, [[John J. Keane (Olympics)|John J. Keane]] attempted to unite various sports associations under an Irish Olympic Committee.<ref name=\"iando432\">Ireland and Olympism, p.432</ref> Many sports had rival bodies, one [[Unionism in Ireland|Unionist]] and affiliated to a United Kingdom parent, the other [[Irish republicanism|Republican]] and opposed to any link with [[Great Britain]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}} Keane proposed that a separate Irish delegation, marching under the [[Union Flag]], should participate at the [[1920 Summer Olympics]] in [[Antwerp]].<ref name=\"iando432\"/> At the time the [[Irish War of Independence]] was under way, and the IOC rejected Keane's proposal, pending the settlement of the underlying political situation.<ref name=\"iando432\"/>\n\n==Political issues==\nThe OCI has always used the name \"Ireland\", and has claimed to represent the entire [[Ireland|island of Ireland]], even though [[Northern Ireland]] remained part of the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cronin|first=Mike|author2=David Doyle |author3=Liam O'Callaghan |title='Foreign Fields and Foreigners on the Field: Irish Sport, Inclusion and Assimilation'|journal=International Journal of the History of Sport|publisher=Routledge|volume=25|issue=8|pages=1010\u20131030 |doi=10.1080/09523360802106754}}</ref>  These points have been contentious, particularly from the 1930s to the 1950s in [[Track and field athletics|athletics]], and until the 1970s in [[bicycle racing|cycling]].<ref name=\"sullivan\"/>\n\n===Northern Ireland===\n[[File:Flag of the President of Ireland.svg|thumb|Proposed Olympic flag for Ireland, the [[arms of Ireland]].<ref name=\"armsasflag\"/>]]\nThe governing bodies in the island of Ireland of many sports had been established prior to [[Partition of Ireland|the 1922 partition]], and most have remained as single all-island bodies since then. Recognition of the [[Irish border]] was politically contentious and unpopular with [[Irish nationalism|Irish nationalists]].  The [[National Athletic and Cycling Association]] (Ireland), or NACA(I), was formed in 1922 by the merger of rival all-island associations, and affiliated to both the [[International Association of Athletics Federations|International Amateur Athletics Federation]] (IAAF) and [[Union Cycliste Internationale]] (UCI).<ref name=\"sullivan\"/> When Northern Ireland athletes were selected for the [[Ireland at the 1928 Summer Olympics|1928 games]], the possibility was raised of using an \"all-Ireland banner\" as the team flag, rather than the [[Irish tricolour]] which [[Unionism in Ireland|unionists]] disavowed.<ref>{{cite news|title=An Irishman's Diary: The Olympic Games|date=23 May 1928|work=The Irish Times|page=4}}</ref> J. J. Keane stated that it was too late to change the flag registered with the IOC, but was hopeful that the [[coat of arms of Ireland]] would be adopted afterwards.<ref name=\"armsasflag\">{{cite news|title=Olympic Games; Question of Irish flag |date=30 May 1928|work=The Irish Times|page=7}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925, some Northern Ireland athletics clubs left NACA(I) and in 1930 formed the Northern Ireland Amateur Athletics Association, which later formed the [[British Athletic Federation]] (BAF) with the English and Scottish Amateur Athletics Associations.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/> The BAF then replaced the (English) AAA as Britain's member of the IAAF, and moved that all members should be delimited by political boundaries.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/> This was not agreed in time for the [[1932 Summer Olympics]] \u2014at which two NACA(I) athletes won gold medals for Ireland\u2014 but was agreed at the IAAF\u2019s 1934 congress.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/>  The NACA(I) refused to comply and was suspended in 1935, thus missing the [[1936 Summer Olympics|1936 Berlin Olympics]].<ref name=\"sullivan\"/>  The OCI decided to boycott the Games completely in protest.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Kr\u00fcger|first=Arnd |author2=William J. Murray|title=The Nazi Olympics: sport, politics and appeasement in the 1930s |publisher=University of Illinois Press|year=2003 |page=230 |isbn=0-252-02815-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s5ntIQv0W5IC&lpg=PA230&dq=1936%20olympics%20%22irish%20free%20state%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=0&pg=PA230#v=onepage&q=1936%20olympics%20%22irish%20free%20state%22&f=false }}</ref>\n\nThe UCI likewise suspended the NACA(I) for refusing to confine itself to the Irish Free State. The athletics and cycling wings of the NACA(I) split into two all-island bodies, and separate Irish Free State bodies split from each and secured affiliation to the IAAF and UCI. These splits were not fully resolved until the 1990s. The \"[[Partitionism|partitionist]]\" Amateur Athletic Union of \u00c9ire (AAUE) affiliated to the IAAF, but the all-Ireland NACA(I) remained affiliated to the OCI.  The IOC allowed AAU\u00c9 athletes to compete for [[Ireland at the 1948 Summer Olympics|Ireland at the 1948 London Olympics]], but the rest of the OCI delegation shunned them.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/>  At that games, two swimmers from Northern Ireland were prevented from competing in the OCI team.  This was a [[FINA]] ruling rather than an IOC rule; Danny Taylor from Belfast was allowed by [[International Rowing Federation|FISA]] to compete in the rowing.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/> The entire swimming squad withdrew,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/07/31/archives/eire-withdraws-swimming-squad-ban-on-two-athletes-born-in-northern.html|title=Eire withdraws swimming squad; Ban on Two Athletes Born in Northern Ireland Impels Protest at Olympics|date=31 July 1948 |work=New York Times|page=10, sports|accessdate=13 February 2010}}</ref> but the rest of the team competed.<ref name=\"offrpt1948\">{{cite book|title=Official Report of the Organising Committee for the XIV Olympiad |location=London |year=1951 |url=http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1948/OR1948.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716035822/http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1948/OR1948.pdf |archivedate=16 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nSome athletes born in what had become the Republic of Ireland continued to compete for the British team.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/> In 1952, new IOC President [[Avery Brundage]] and new OCI delegate [[Michael Morris, 3rd Baron Killanin|Lord Killanin]] agreed that people from Northern Ireland would in future be allowed to compete in any sport on the OCI team.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/><ref name=\"bbc2004\"/> In [[Irish nationality law]], birth in Northern Ireland grants a citizenship entitlement similar to birth within the Republic of Ireland itself. In 1956, Killanin stated that both the OCI and the BOA \"quite rightly\" judged eligibility based on citizenship laws.<ref name=\"it19561005\"/>  \nUCI and IAAF affiliated bodies were subsequently affiliated to the OCI, thus regularising the position of Irish competitors in those sports at the Olympics.  Members of the all-Ireland National Cycling Association (NCA) with [[Irish Republicanism|Irish Republican]] sympathies twice interfered with the Olympic road race in protest against the UCI-affiliated Irish Cycling Federation (ICF). [[Cycling at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|In 1956]], three members caused a 13-minute delay at the start.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hYQOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bIADAAAAIBAJ&dq=olympic%20cycling%20irish&pg=6957%2C2971583|title=Another rhubarb delays Olympic cycling event|author=Associated Press|date=7 December 1956|work=St. Petersburg Times|page=14|accessdate=13 February 2010}}</ref> Seven were arrested [[Cycling at the 1972 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|in 1972]]; three  had delayed the start<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=acwzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1pADAAAAIBAJ&dq=olympic%20cycling%20irish&pg=1412%2C1744537|title=Rebel cyclists sent marching|author=AAP|date=8 September 1972|work=The Age|page=15|accessdate=13 February 2010|location=Melbourne}}</ref> and the other four joined mid-race to ambush ICF competitor Noel Taggart, causing a minor pileup.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F00A10FD395E127A93CAA91782D85F468785F9|title=7 I.R.A. cyclists 'invade' Olympics; Rebels Say Their Team Is Better Than the Regulars, Then Try to Prove It|author=AP|date=8 September 1972 |work=New York Times |page=23, Sports|accessdate=13 February 2010}}</ref> This happened days after the [[Munich massacre|murders of Israeli athletes]] and at the height of [[the Troubles]] in Northern Ireland; the negative publicity helped precipitate an end to the NCA\u2013ICF feud.<ref>{{cite book|last=Coakley|first=John |author2=Liam O'Dowd|title=Crossing the border: new relationships between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland |publisher=Irish Academic Press|year=2007|page=232 |isbn=0-7165-2922-X }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Irish Hockey Union]] joined the OCI in 1949,<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.la84foundation.org/OlympicInformationCenter/OlympicReview/1973/ore70/ore70m.pdf#page=10 |title=Ireland and Olympism |journal=Olympic Review |format=PDF |accessdate=20 February 2009 |issue=70\u201371 |date=September\u2013October 1973 |page=440}}</ref> and the [[Ireland men's national field hockey team|Ireland team]] in non-Olympic competitions is selected on an all-island basis.<ref name=\"sugden\">{{cite book |last=Sugden |first=John |author2=Alan Bairner |title=Sport, sectarianism and society in a divided Ireland |publisher=Leicester University Press |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hBUmfaATHBgC&pg=PA63 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |year=1995 |pages=63\u201367 |chapter=British Sports and Irish identity |isbn=0-7185-0018-0}}</ref> Until 1992 the IHU was not invited to the [[Field hockey at the Summer Olympics|Olympic hockey tournament]],<ref name=\"sugden\"/> while Northern Irish hockey players like [[Stephen Martin (field hockey)|Stephen Martin]] played on the [[Great Britain men's national field hockey team|British Olympic men's team]].<ref name=\"sugden\"/> [[Field hockey at the 1992 Summer Olympics|In 1992]], invitation was replaced by an Olympic qualifying tournament, which the IHU/IHA has entered, despite some opposition from Northern Irish members.<ref name=\"sugden\"/> Northern Irish players can play for Ireland or Britain, and can switch affiliation subject to [[International Hockey Federation]] clearance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/hockey/hockey-ulster-duo-get-green-light-for-gb-15080507.html|title=Hockey: Ulster duo get green light for GB|last=Hamilton|first=Graham|date=11 February 2011|work=[[The Belfast Telegraph]]|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> The [[Irish Ladies Hockey Union]] has entered the Olympics since [[Field hockey at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984]], and [[Field hockey at the 1980 Summer Olympics|in 1980]] suspended Northern Irish players who elected to play for the [[Great Britain women's national field hockey team|British women's team]].<ref name=\"sugden\"/>\n\nThrough to the 1960s, Ireland was represented [[Equestrian at the Summer Olympics#Show jumping in the Olympic Games|in showjumping]] only by members of the [[Irish Army Equitation School]], as the all-island civilian equestrian governing body was unwilling to compete under the Republic's [[Flag of Ireland|flag]] and [[Amhr\u00e1n na bhFiann|anthem]].<ref>[http://debates.oireachtas.ie/dail/1963/07/03/00025.asp D\u00e1il debates Vol.204 No.2 p.25] Oireachtas</ref>\n\nIn November 2003, the OCI discovered that the [[British Olympic Association]] (BOA) had been using ''Northern Ireland'' in the text of its \"Team Members Agreement\" document since the [[Great Britain at the 2002 Winter Olympics|2002 Games]].<ref name=\"it200040128\">{{cite news |last=Watterson |first=Johnny |date=28 January 2004 |title=Dispute could jeopardise London bid |page=23  |newspaper=Irish Times  |location=Dublin }}</ref> Its objection was made public in January 2004. The BOA responded that \"Unbeknown to each other both the OCI and BOA have constitutions approved by the IOC acknowledging territorial responsibility for Northern Ireland\", the BOA constitution dating from 1981.<ref name=\"it200040128\"/> OCI president [[Pat Hickey (sports administrator)|Pat Hickey]] claimed the IOC's copy of the BOA constitution had \"question marks\" against mentions of Northern Ireland (and [[Gibraltar]]);<ref>{{cite news |last=Mooney |first=Brendan  |date=29 January 2004 |title=Hickey: Northern Irish athletes are free to represent Ireland at Olympics  |newspaper=Irish Examiner |location=Cork }}</ref> an IOC spokesperson said \"Through an error we have given both national Olympic committees rights over the same area.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Bright |first=Richard |date=21 February 2004 |title=British agree on Irish issue  |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |page=7 }}</ref> The [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Games]] host was to be selected in July 2004 and so, to prevent the dispute harming the [[London bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics|London bid]], its director [[Barbara Cassani]] and the [[Blair ministry|Blair government]] secured agreement by which ''Northern Ireland'' was removed from BOA documents and marketing materials.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beard |first=Matthew |date=18 February 2004 |title=Olympic Games: BOA moves to resolve turf war with Irish  |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |page=47 }}</ref><ref name=\"bbc2004\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympics_2004/olympics_2012/3433557.stm |title=Irish and GB in Olympic row|date=27 January 2004|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=27 February 2010}}</ref> Northern Ireland athletes retain the right to compete for Britain.<ref name=\"bbc2004\"/>  \n\n[[File:Predominant passport held northern ireland.png|thumb|Most commonly held passport in Northern Ireland (2011 Census) ]]\nIn October 2004, [[Andrew McIntosh, Baron McIntosh of Haringey|Lord McIntosh of Haringey]] told the [[House of Lords]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/2004/oct/21/olympic-games-participation|title=Olympic Games Participation|date=21 October 2004|work=House of Lords debates|publisher=Hansard|pages=vol 665 c99WA |nopp=y|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n{{quote|The longstanding practice relating to athletes in Northern Ireland who qualify for participation at the Olympic Games is that an athlete born in Northern Ireland who qualifies for participation at the Olympic Games and who holds a [[UK passport]], may opt for selection by either Team GB or Ireland. The British Olympic Association (BOA) and the Olympic Council for Ireland (OCI) have recently confirmed this agreement.}}\nBy contrast, OCI officers Pat Hickey and Dermot Sherlock told an [[Oireachtas]] committee in 2008:<ref name=\"oireachtasTOJ2008\">{{cite web|url=http://debates.oireachtas.ie/TOJ/2008/07/16/00004.asp#N107|title=Beijing Olympics: Discussion with Olympic Council of Ireland.|date=16 July 2008|work=Joint Committee on Arts, Sport, Tourism, Community, Rural and Gaeltacht Affairs|publisher=Oireachtas|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref>\n{{quote|If someone is entitled to an [[Irish passport]] and is in possession of that passport, he or she can qualify to compete for Ireland as long as he or she has not competed for some other country in a previous Olympic Games. If he or she had competed for another country previously, we might allow him or her to compete for Ireland...The Irish passport is used as the measurement.[...]As people from Northern Ireland can choose whether to have an Irish or a British passport, athletes from that part of the world can choose whether to compete for Ireland or Britain.}}\nHickey also said:<ref name=\"oireachtasTOJ2008\"/>\n{{quote|The council is proud that, like the [[Ireland national rugby union team|Irish rugby team]], it represents the island of Ireland. Ireland is unusual, in Olympic terms. The council is not the Olympic committee of the Republic of Ireland - it is the Olympic Council of Ireland. We have responsibility for the North of Ireland. We can thank my predecessor, Lord Killanin, for that.}}\n\nIn 2012, [[Stephen Martin (field hockey)|Stephen Martin]], who has been an executive at both the OCI and the BOA, said \"Team GB is a brand name. Just like Team Ireland. The British and Irish Olympic committees are seen by the International Olympic Committees as having joint rights over Northern Ireland.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=GB or not GB -- that is the question|last=Little|first=Ivan|date=10 Aug 2012|work=Belfast Telegraph|page=6|location=Belfast}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[rugby sevens]] was added to the Olympic programme [[Rugby sevens at the Summer Olympics|starting in 2016]]. While [[World Rugby]] states players from Northern Ireland are eligible to compete on the [[Great Britain national rugby sevens team|Great Britain team]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldrugby.org/news/155038|title=Regulation 8 Explanatory Guidelines|website=World Rugby|pages=paragraphs 12, 13|nopp=y|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref> the [[Irish Rugby Football Union]] (IRFU) director of rugby said in 2011 that \"with the agreement of the [English, Scottish, and Welsh] unions\" the \"de facto position\" was that Northern Ireland players must represent [[Ireland national rugby sevens team|an IRFU team]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sport/irfu-rule-out-ulster-players-for-british-team-1.571714|title=IRFU rule out Ulster players for British team|last=Watterson|first=Johnny|date=14 April 2011|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref> In 2010 ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''  opined that the IRFU would be entitled to refuse to release players under contract to it, but not to prohibit Northern Ireland players based outside Ireland; but that the issue needed to be handled \"with extreme sensitivity\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/7761877/Officials-to-discuss-Team-GB-Olympic-Sevens-team.html|title=Officials to discuss Team GB Olympic Sevens team|date=24 May 2010|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Name of the country===\n{{see also|Names of the Irish state}}\nThe OCI sees itself as representing the island rather than the state, and hence uses the name \"Ireland\".<ref name=\"sullivan\"/> It changed its own name from \"Irish Olympic Council\" to \"Olympic Council of Ireland\" in 1952 to reinforce this point.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/> At the time, [[Michael Morris, 3rd Baron Killanin|Lord Killanin]] had become OCI President and delegate to the IOC, and was trying to reverse the IOC's policy of referring to the OCI's team by using an appellation of the state rather than the island.  While the name \"Ireland\" had been unproblematic at the 1924 and 1928 Games, after 1930, the IOC sometimes used \"Irish Free State\". IOC President [[Henri de Baillet-Latour]] supported the principle of delimitation by political borders.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/> At the 1932 Games, [[Eoin O'Duffy]] persuaded the Organisers to switch from \"Irish Free State\" to \"Ireland\" shortly before the Opening Ceremony.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/>  After the [[Constitution of Ireland|1937 Constitution]] took effect, the IOC switched to \"[[\u00c9ire|Eire]]\"; this conformed to British practice, although within the state so designated the use of \"Eire\" soon became deprecated.  At the opening ceremony of the [[1948 Summer Olympics]], teams marched in alphabetical order of their country's name in English; the OCI team was told to move from the I's to the E's.<ref name=\"sullivan\"/> After the [[Republic of Ireland Act]] came into effect in 1949, British policy was to use \"Republic of Ireland\" rather than \"Eire\". In 1951, the IOC made the same switch at its Vienna conference, after IOC member [[David Cecil, 6th Marquess of Exeter|Lord Burghley]] had consulted the British [[Foreign Office]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Requ\u00eate de l\u2019Eire. Bulletin du Comit\u00e9 Internationale Olympique  |date=June 1951 |publisher=IOC |location=Lausanne |issue=27 |page=12 |language=French |url= http://www.la84foundation.org/OlympicInformationCenter/RevueOlympique/1951/BDCF27/BDCF27e.pdf }}</ref> An OCI request to change this to \"Ireland\" was rejected in 1952.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Extract of the 46th Session of the International Olympic Committee, Oslo, 12th to 13th February, 1952. Bulletin du Comit\u00e9 Internationale Olympique |date=March 1952 |publisher=IOC |location=Lausanne |issue=32 |pages=10\u201311 |url=http://www.la84foundation.org/OlympicInformationCenter/OlympicReview/1952/BDCE32/BDCE32d.pdf }}</ref> The name \"Ireland\" was accepted just before the [[1956 Summer Olympics|1956 Olympics in Melbourne]].<ref name=\"sullivan\"/><ref name=\"it19561005\">{{cite news|title=Irish athletes to compete in Olympics as 'Ireland'|date=5 October 1956|work=The Irish Times|page=1}}</ref> The OCI had argued that this was the name in the state's own Constitution, and that all the OCI's  affiliated sports except the [[Football Association of Ireland]] were all-island bodies.<ref name=\"it19561005\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of flag bearers for Ireland at the Olympics]]\n* [[:Category:Olympic competitors for Ireland]]\n* [[Ireland at the Paralympics]]\n* [[Ireland at the British Empire Games]]\n* [[2016 Summer Olympics ticket scandal]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite journal|last=Hunt|first=Tom|year=2015|title=\u2018In our case, it seems obvious the British Organising Committee piped the tune\u2019: the campaign for recognition of \u2018Ireland\u2019 in the Olympic Movement, 1935\u20131956|journal=Sport in Society|volume=18|issue=7|pages=835\u2013852|issn=1743-0437|doi=10.1080/17430437.2014.990689}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Llewellyn|first=Matthew P.|year=2015|title=For a \u2018United\u2019 Kingdom and a \u2018Greater\u2019 Britain: the British Olympic Association and the limitations and contestations of \u2018Britishness\u2019|journal=Sport in Society|volume=18|issue=7|pages=765\u2013782|issn=1743-0437|doi=10.1080/17430437.2014.990687}}\n* {{cite book|last=MacCarthy|first=Kevin|title=Gold, Silver and Green: The Irish Olympic Journey 1896-1924|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ic9ZPgAACAAJ|accessdate=28 May 2013|date=2010-03-30|publisher=Cork University Press|isbn=9781859184585}}\n* {{cite web |title=Ireland |publisher=International Olympic Committee |url=http://www.olympic.org/ireland |work=Countries |accessdate=19 April 2016 }}\n* {{cite web |title=Ireland |publisher=International Olympic Committee |url=http://www.olympic.org/athletes?search=1&countryname=ireland |work=Olympic Medal Winners |accessdate=19 April 2016 }}\n* {{cite web|title=Ireland |publisher=Sports-Reference.com |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/IRL |work=Olympics > Countries |accessdate=19 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422162517/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/IRL/ |archivedate=22 April 2016 }}\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IOC medals|NOC=IRL}}\n\n{{Nations at the Olympics}}\n{{National sports teams of Ireland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ireland At The Olympics}}\n[[Category:Ireland at the Olympics| ]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of Ireland|Olympics]]\n", "name_user": "JASpencer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBefore independence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ireland_at_the_Olympics"}
{"title_page": "Hilarie Burton", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hilarie Burton\n| image              = Hilarie Burton Gitmo (crop).jpg\n| caption            = Burton in June 2008\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1982|7|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Sterling, Virginia]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[New York University]] <br />[[Fordham University]]\n| occupation         = Actress, producer, television host\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Jeffrey Dean Morgan]]|October 5, 2019}}\n| children           = 2\n| yearsactive        = 1999\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''[https://greetingsglobal.com/hilarie-burton-height-age-weight-bio/ Hilarie Burton Morgan]''' (born July 1, 1982) is an American actress and producer. A former host of MTV's ''[[Total Request Live]]'', she portrayed [[Peyton Sawyer]] on [[The WB]]/[[The CW|CW]] drama ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'' for six seasons (2003\u20132009). Burton gained wider recognition with leading roles in the films ''[[Our Very Own (2005 film)|Our Very Own]]'', ''[[Solstice (film)|Solstice]]'', and ''[[The List (2007 film)|The List]]''. She starred as [[Sara Ellis (White Collar)|Sara Ellis]] on the [[USA Network|USA]] crime drama ''[[White Collar (TV series)|White Collar]]'' (2010\u20132013); and, in 2013, she had a recurring role as Dr. Lauren Boswell on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] medical drama ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]''. In 2014, she appeared in the short-lived [[ABC (U.S. TV network)|ABC]] drama series ''[[Forever (2014 TV series)|Forever]]'' as Molly Dawes, and a recurring role in the short-lived [[CBS]] [[sci-fi]] [[drama]] series ''[[Extant (TV series)|Extant]]'' as Anna Schaefer in 2015. From 2016 until 2017, Burton recurred as [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] Agent Karen Palmer on the [[Fox (TV network)|Fox]] television series ''[[Lethal Weapon (TV series)|Lethal Weapon]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBurton was born in [[Sterling, Virginia]]. Her father is a veteran of the US Army.<ref>{{cite web|last=DeHority|first=Sam|title=Are You Man Enough for Hilarie Burton?|url=http://www.mensfitness.com/women/dating-advice/are-you-man-enough-for-hilarie-burton|work=[[Men's Fitness]]|accessdate=August 5, 2013}}</ref> and her mother is a real estate agent.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ingram|first1=Hunter|title=Hilarie Burton, Stephen Colletti reminisce about \u2018One Tree Hill\u2019 during adorable Q&A|url=http://wilmonfilm.blogs.starnewsonline.com/17065/hilarie-burton-stephen-colletti-reminisce-about-one-tree-hill-during-adorable-qa/?tc=ar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222153917/http://wilmonfilm.blogs.starnewsonline.com/17065/hilarie-burton-stephen-colletti-reminisce-about-one-tree-hill-during-adorable-qa/?tc=ar|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 22, 2015|website=[[Starnewsonline.com]]|accessdate=August 5, 2015|date=March 28, 2015}}</ref> She is the eldest of four children with three brothers. She graduated from [[Park View High School (Loudoun County, Virginia)|Park View High School]] in 2000, where she was student council treasurer her sophomore year,<ref>Heritage: Park View High School Yearbook (1998)</ref> vice-president her junior year,<ref>Heritage: Park View High School Yearbook (1999)</ref> and captain of the cheerleading squad, student council president, and homecoming queen her senior year.<ref name=\"bio\">[http://www.tv.com/hilarie-burton/person/134474/biography.html Hilarie Burton- TV.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080710140222/http://www.tv.com/hilarie-burton/person/134474/biography.html |date=July 10, 2008 }} Retrieved January 19, 2007.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Media personality===\nBurton's first big break came when working as a [[VJ (media personality)|VJ]] for MTV's ''[[Total Request Live]] (TRL)''. She was supposed to be a guest commentator for one segment, but producers decided to offer her a permanent job. Burton went on to present at the [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards]] and MTV's ''Iced Out New Year's Eve''. Burton went on to portray herself on [[The WB]] drama ''[[Dawson's Creek]]'' in 2002, which marked her television debut.\n\nIn October 2017, when news of the [[Harvey Weinstein scandal]] broke, Burton [[Twitter|retweeted]] a 2003 video clip from ''TRL Uncensored'' in which [[Ben Affleck]] squeezed her breast on air. This was in response to a fan tweet that quipped, \"[Affleck] also grabbed Hilarie Burton's breasts on TRL once. Everyone forgot though.\" Burton replied, \"I didn't forget [about it] ... I was a kid.\" Affleck, who'd just publicly criticized Weinstein, subsequently responded on Twitter to apologize to Burton.<ref name=\"Gonzalez\">{{Cite news|last=Gonzalez|first=Sandra|title=Ben Affleck apologizes for groping Hilarie Burton on camera|work=[[CNN]]|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=November 22, 2017|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/10/11/entertainment/ben-affleck-apology/index.html}}</ref> When asked about the incident a month later on ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'', Affleck said, \"I don't remember it, but I absolutely apologize for it. I certainly don't think she's lying or making it up.'\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/ben-affleck-talks-sexual-misconduct-accusations-on-colbert-w512097 |title=Stephen Colbert Confronts Ben Affleck on Sexual Misconduct Accusations |work=[[Rolling Stone]]| last=Leight|first=Elias|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Acting and producing===\nBurton was cast in The WB drama series ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'' as [[Peyton Sawyer]], an independent visual and musical artist and cheerleader, in April 2003. The series premiered on September 23, 2003, and went on to be the network's top rated program of the year. The role was considered Burton's breakout role and is her best known to date. For her role in the series, Burton was featured on the cover of ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'', ''[[American Cheerleader Magazine]]'' and ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''. Her performance received critical praise and she earned three [[Teen Choice Award]] nominations.<ref name=bio/> In May 2009, [[The CW]] announced Burton would not be returning for the show's seventh season based on her own decision not to return, contrary to rumors she left due to salary issues.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.tvguide.com/News/Murray-Burton-exit-1006006.aspx|title=Breaking: Two Stars Exit One Tree Hill|publisher=TVGuide.com|accessdate=May 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOne Tree Hill heightened Burton's public profile: in May 2007, she was ranked #77 in ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]''{{'}}s \"Hot 100 List of 2007\".<ref name=\"Maxim\">[http://www.maximonline.com/slideshows/index.aspx?slideId=3624&imgCollectId=190 Hilarie Burton of 2007 Hot 100 Maxim] Retrieved February 1, 2007.</ref> She also appeared on the cover of the November 2006 edition of ''Maxim'' with ''One Tree Hill'' co-stars [[Sophia Bush]] and [[Danneel Ackles|Danneel Harris]]. In previous years, Burton ranked #2 on ''[[Femme Fatales (magazine)|Femme Fatales]]''{{'}} \"The 50 Sexiest Women of 2005\", and #12 on [[Much Music]]'s \"20 Hottest Women of 2003\".\n\nWhile still a One Tree Hill cast member, Burton made her feature film debut opposite [[Allison Janney]] and [[Cheryl Hines]] in the 2005 well-reviewed drama ''[[Our Very Own (2005 film)|Our Very Own]]'' which centered on five small-town teenagers who dream of a better life. Burton and her co-stars received the \"Outstanding Ensemble Acting\" award at the prestigious [[Sarasota Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cwtv.com/shows/one-tree-hill/cast/hilarie-burton|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012233729/http://www.cwtv.com/shows/one-tree-hill/cast/hilarie-burton|url-status=dead|title=Hilarie Burton cast bio on The WB|archivedate=October 12, 2007|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> Burton appeared in the 2007 [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] drama ''[[Normal Adolescent Behavior]]'' which followed a group of friends who are in a six-way polyfidelitous relationship. That same year, Burton co-starred in the supernatural horror film ''[[Solstice (film)|Solstice]]'' opposite [[Amanda Seyfried]] and [[Elisabeth Harnois]]. Burton also created her own production company, Southern Gothic Production (SoGoPro) in 2007, along with Nick Gray, Kelly Tenney, James Burton, and Meg Mortimer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://southerngothicprod.com/aboutus.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-05-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090428112358/http://www.southerngothicprod.com/aboutus.htm |archivedate=April 28, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"sogopro.com\">{{cite web|url=http://sogopro.com/ |title=Southern Gothic Productions \u2013 Home Page |publisher=Sogopro.com |date= |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://southerngothicproductions.blogspot.com/ |title=Blogger |publisher=Southerngothicproductions.blogspot.com |date= |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Burton appeared in both the [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]] drama ''[[The Secret Life of Bees (film)|The Secret Life of Bees]]'', as the deceased mother of [[Dakota Fanning]]'s character, and the limited release thriller ''[[The List (2008 film)|The List]]''. Burton was next cast in the film ''[[Bloodworth]]'' opposite [[Hilary Duff]] and [[Val Kilmer]], an adaptation of the novel ''Provinces of Night'' by [[William Gay (author)|William Gay]]. The film premiered after her exit from One Tree Hill, at the 2010 [[Santa Barbara International Film Festival]], but made little money in limited release. Burton won a recurring arc in the [[USA Network]] crime drama series ''[[White Collar (TV series)|White Collar]]'' in 2010 as Sara Ellis, an insurance investigator in the second season. She was upgraded to a series regular in 2011 for the third season, but switched back to the recurring cast in the fourth season.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.tvguide.com/News/White-Collar-Burton-1029011.aspx|title= White Collar Promotes Hilarie Burton to Series Regular|publisher=TVGuide.com|accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> 2012 saw Burton guest-starring on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] police comedy-drama [[Castle (TV series)|''Castle'']] (season 4, episode 13) as a reality television star who is accused murder.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvline.com/2011/11/23/hilarie-burton-castle-season-4-episode-13/|title=''Castle'' scoop: Hilarie Burton excited to tackle a 'radically different' kind of role|date=November 23, 2011|author=Matt Webb Mitovich|work=TVLine.com|accessdate=February 6, 2013}}</ref> Next came a recurring role in the ABC medical drama ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' for the final three episodes of the 2013 [[Grey's Anatomy (season 9)|ninth season]], as Dr. Lauren Boswell. That fall, Burton had a recurring role on the short-lived [[CBS]] drama ''[[Hostages (American TV series)|Hostages]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hostages/IMDB|url=https://pro-labs.imdb.com/title/tt3096660/|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref> Burton reunited with ''One Tree Hill'' co-star Tyler Hilton for a recurring role on CBS sci-fi drama ''[[Extant (TV series)|Extant]]'' in 2015. Burton appeared as the DEA agent love interest of main character Martin Riggs on ''[[Lethal Weapon (TV series)|Lethal Weapon]]'' from the seventh episode of the first season in 2016 through the third episode of the second season in 2017.\n\nIn November 2017, Burton spoke out in light of charges that ''One Tree Hill'' creator [[Mark Schwahn]] had sexually harassed some of the female crew, alleging that she had also been sexually harassed by Schwahn.<ref name=\"Holloway\">{{Cite news|last=Holloway|first=Daniel|title=\u2018One Tree Hill\u2019 Cast, Crew Detail Assault, Harassment Claims Against Mark Schwahn (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=November 18, 2017|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/one-tree-hill-mark-schwahn-harassment-assault-1202617918/}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:US Navy 081206-N-3346C-012 Chief Master-at-Arms Michael Minotto explains the functions of the M4 Battle Rifle to actress Hilarie Burton.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Burton holding an [[M4 carbine]] during a [[United Service Organizations|USO]] visit.]]\nDuring her time on ''One Tree Hill'', Burton resided in [[Wilmington, North Carolina]], where the show was filmed.<ref name=\"TVGuide.com\">{{cite magazine|title=Hilarie Burton: Biography|magazine=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=April 29, 2009|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/hilarie-burton/bio/190035}}</ref><ref name=bio/<ref name=\"TVGuide.com\"/>\n\nIn 2009, Burton began a relationship with actor [[Jeffrey Dean Morgan]]. The couple's son was born in March 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/momsbabies/news/jeffrey-dean-morgan-hilarie-burton-welcome-baby-201065 |title=Jeffrey Dean Morgan, Hilarie Burton Welcome Baby |magazine=Us Weekly |date=May 6, 2010|accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eonline.com/news/marc_malkin/jeffrey_dean_morgan_hilarie_burton_talk/275265 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120715205633/http://uk.eonline.com/news/marc_malkin/jeffrey_dean_morgan_hilarie_burton_talk/275265 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 15, 2012 |title=Jeffrey Dean Morgan and Hilarie Burton Talk Baby Son Gus, Parenthood: \"It's Been Spectacular\" |date=November 15, 2011 |author=Marc Malkin |publisher=E!Online |accessdate=May 5, 2012}}</ref>  On March 6, 2018, Burton announced on Instagram that their daughter was born in February 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bf_cxoPhaq3/|title=Hilarie Burton on Instagram: \"As some of you know, @jeffreydeanmorgan is off in Europe getting ready to do some big conventions. And he's self aware enough to know his\u2026\"|website=Instagram|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> The couple married on October 5, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Byrne |first1=Suzy |title=Jeffrey Dean Morgan and Hilarie Burton announce they\u2019re married in supersweet posts on Instagram |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/jeffrey-dean-morgan-and-hilarie-burton-announce-theyre-married-in-supersweet-posts-on-instagram-163613860.html |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |accessdate=7 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Soundtracks===\n* ''[[One Tree Hill Soundtracks#The Road Mix|The Road Mix: Music from the Television Series One Tree Hill, Volume 3]]'' (2007)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Our Very Own (2005 film)|Our Very Own]]''\n| Bobbie Chester\n| Film debut\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Normal Adolescent Behavior]]''\n| Ryan\n| \n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Solstice (film)|Solstice]]''\n| Alicia\n| \n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The List (2007 film)|The List]]''\n| Jo Johnston\n| \n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Secret Life of Bees (film)|The Secret Life of Bees]]''\n| Deborah Owens\n| \n|-\n| 2009\n| ''The True-Love Tale of Boyfriend & Girlfriend''\n| Boyfriend\n| A Southern Gothic Production\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Bloodworth]]''\n| Hazel\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2000\u20132004\n| ''[[Total Request Live]]''\n| Herself\n| Co-host\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Dawson's Creek]]''\n| VJ Hilarie\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2003\u20132009\n| ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]''\n| [[Peyton Sawyer]]\n| Main cast; 130 Episodes {{small|(Seasons 1\u20136)}}\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''MTV's Iced Out New Year's Eve''\n| Herself\n| Host\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''MTV Does Miami''\n| Herself\n| Co-host\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[MTV Diary]]''\n| Herself\n| Alongside ''One Tree Hill'' cast\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[The Real World: Las Vegas]]''\n| Herself\n| Reunion Host: ''[[The Real World: Las Vegas#After filming|7 The Hard Way]]''\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''Pepsi S