arie_Burton"}
{"title_page": "Adam Creighton (journalist)", "text_new": "'''Adam Creighton''' is an [[Australia]]n journalist and Economics Editor of ''[[The Australian]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/author/Adam%20Creighton?nk=107d7b16607a747cceab5e084f11d693-1582236604|title=Adam Creighton {{!}} Author at The Australian|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\nHe is regarded as holding generally [[Conservatism|conservative]] views and has been called an 'arch-neoliberal'.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wilson|first=Jason|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/feb/03/the-rightwing-reaction-to-queensland-shows-they-want-to-rule-not-govern|title=The rightwing reaction to Queensland shows they want to rule, not govern {{!}} Jason Wilson|date=2015-02-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-20|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nHe is a contributor to [[Sky News Australia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skynews.com.au/details/_6133263286001|title=General Motors ultimately 'doesn't care about Australian jobs'|website=Sky News Australia|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> and has written for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/author/adam-creighton|title=Adam Creighton - News, Articles, Biography, Photos  - WSJ.com|website=WSJ|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> He is a member of the Advisory Council of the [[National Archives of Australia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.naa.gov.au/about-us/our-organisation/advisory-council/mr-adam-creighton|title=Mr Adam Creighton {{!}} naa.gov.au|website=www.naa.gov.au|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\nCreighton has received several awards for his writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prosper.org.au/2017/09/ej-craigie-award-winner-adam-creighton/|title=EJ Craigie Award Winner \u2013 Adam Creighton {{!}} Prosper Australia|last=Fitzgerald|first=Karl|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Adam Creighton wins Citi Journalism Award for Excellence|date=30 April 2015|work=The Australian|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citigroup.com/australia/awards/previous.html|title=Citi {{!}} Australia {{!}} Media {{!}} Citi Journalism Awards for Excellence {{!}} Previous Journalism Award winners|website=www.citigroup.com|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{improve categories|date=February 2020}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creighton, Adam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian economists]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales alumni]]\n\n\n{{Australia-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Adam Creighton''' is an [[Australia|Australian]] journalist and Economics Editor of ''[[The Australian]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/author/Adam%20Creighton?nk=107d7b16607a747cceab5e084f11d693-1582236604|title=Adam Creighton {{!}} Author at The Australian|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> \n\nHe is regarded as holding generally [[Conservatism|conservative]] views and has been called an 'arch-neoliberal'.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wilson|first=Jason|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/feb/03/the-rightwing-reaction-to-queensland-shows-they-want-to-rule-not-govern|title=The rightwing reaction to Queensland shows they want to rule, not govern {{!}} Jason Wilson|date=2015-02-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-20|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nHe is a contributor to [[Sky News Australia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skynews.com.au/details/_6133263286001|title=General Motors ultimately 'doesn't care about Australian jobs'|website=Sky News Australia|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> and has written for ''[[The Wall Street Journal|The Wall Street Journal.]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/author/adam-creighton|title=Adam Creighton - News, Articles, Biography, Photos  - WSJ.com|website=WSJ|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> He is a member of the Advisory Council of the [[National Archives of Australia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.naa.gov.au/about-us/our-organisation/advisory-council/mr-adam-creighton|title=Mr Adam Creighton {{!}} naa.gov.au|website=www.naa.gov.au|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\nCreighton has received several awards for his writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prosper.org.au/2017/09/ej-craigie-award-winner-adam-creighton/|title=EJ Craigie Award Winner \u2013 Adam Creighton {{!}} Prosper Australia|last=Fitzgerald|first=Karl|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Adam Creighton wins Citi Journalism Award for Excellence|date=30 April 2015|work=The Australian|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citigroup.com/australia/awards/previous.html|title=Citi {{!}} Australia {{!}} Media {{!}} Citi Journalism Awards for Excellence {{!}} Previous Journalism Award winners|website=www.citigroup.com|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Australia-journalist-stub}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creighton, Adam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian economists]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales alumni]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=February 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam_Creighton_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "\u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira\n| image                 = Siza Vieira na Exponor.JPG\n| caption               = \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira in 2012\n| birth_name            = \u00c1lvaro Joaquim de Melo Siza Vieira\n| birth_date            = {{birth-date and age|25 June 1933}}\n| birth_place           = [[Matosinhos]], Portugal\n| death_date            =\n| death_place           =\n| nationality           = Portuguese\n| alma_mater            = [[University of Porto]]\n| awards                = [[Pritzker Prize]] (1992), [[Royal Gold Medal]] (2009), [[International Union of Architects#UIA Gold Medal|UIA Gold Medal]] (2011), Golden Lion for lifetime achievement (2012)\n| significant_buildings = [[Porto School of Architecture|Faculty of Architecture, Porto]]\n| significant_projects  =\n| significant_design    =\n}}\n[[File:Berlin schlesische-str-7 bonjour-tristesse 20050224 p1010029.jpg|thumb|\"[[Bonjour Tristesse (building)|Bonjour Tristesse]]\" apartments, Schlesische Stra\u00dfe, Berlin]]\n\n'''\u00c1lvaro Joaquim de Melo Siza Vieira''', {{small|[[Order of St. James of the Sword|GOSE]], [[Order of Infante D. Henrique|GCIH]], [[Order of Public Instruction (Portugal)|GCIP]]}} (born 25 June 1933), is a Portuguese [[architect]], and [[architectural educator]]. He is internationally known as '''\u00c1lvaro Siza''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8a\u026bv\u0250\u027eu \u02c8siz\u0250}}) and in Portugal as '''Siza Vieira''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8siz\u0250 \u02c8vjej\u027e\u0250}}).\n\n==Early life and education==\nSiza was born in [[Matosinhos]], a small coastal town near [[Porto]].  He graduated in architecture in 1955, at the former School of Fine Arts of the [[University of Porto]], the current [[Porto School of Architecture|FAUP]] &ndash; ''Faculdade de Arquitectura da Universidade do Porto''. \n\n==Career==\nSiza completed his first built work (four houses in Matosinhos) even before ending his studies in 1954, the same year that he first opened his private practice in Porto. Along with [[Fernando T\u00e1vora]], he soon became one of the references of the [[Porto School of Architecture]] where both were teachers. Both architects worked together between 1955 and 1958. Another architect he has collaborated with is [[Eduardo Souto de Moura]], e.g. on Portugal's [[Pavilion of Portugal in Expo'98|flagship pavilions]] at [[Expo '98]] in Lisbon and [[Expo 2000]] in Hannover, as well as on the [[Serpentine Gallery|Serpentine Pavillon]] 2005. Siza's work is often described as \"poetic [[modernism]]\";<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/oct/08/alvaro.siza.riba.prize Jonathan Glancey: ''A Gold Medal for Siza? About time''] in ''The Guardian'', 8 October 2008</ref> he himself has contributed to publications on [[Luis Barrag\u00e1n]].\n\nAmong Siza's earliest works to gain public attention was a public pool complex (named [[Piscinas de Mar\u00e9s]]) he created in the 1960s for Le\u00e7a da Palmeira, a fishing town and summer resort north of Porto. Completed in 1966, both of the two swimming pools (one for children, the other for adults) as well as the building with changing rooms and a cafe are set into the natural rock formation on the site with unobstructed views of the sea.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/27/arts/a-portuguese-wins-pritzker-award.html |title= A Portuguese Wins Pritzker Award |newspaper= [[New York Times]] |date= 27 April 1992}}</ref> In 1977, following the revolution in Portugal, the city government of [[\u00c9vora]] commissioned Siza to plan a housing project in the rural outskirts of the town. It was to be one of several that he would do for SAAL (''Servi\u00e7o de Apoio Ambulat\u00f3rio Local''), the national housing association, consisting of 1,200 low-cost, housing units, some one-story and some two-story row houses, all with courtyards.<ref name=\"Pritzker\"/> He was also a member of the team which reconstructed Chiado, the historic center of Lisbon destroyed by a fire in 1988.\n\nMost of his best known works are located in his hometown Porto: the Boa Nova Tea House (1963), the [[FAUP|Faculty of Architecture]] (1987\u201393), and the [[Serralves Foundation|Serralves Museum of Contemporary Art]] (1997). Since the mid-1970s, Siza has been involved in numerous designs for public housing, public pools,<ref>Patrick Lynch (23 October 2008), [http://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/critics/lvaro-siza-swimming-pools-with-depth/1904917.article \u00c1lvaro Siza: swimming pools with depth] ''The Architect's Journal.''</ref> and universities. Between 1995 and 2009, Siza has been working on an architecture museum on [[Museum Insel Hombroich|Hombroich island]], completed in collaboration with Rudolf Finsterwalder.<ref>Kieran Long (1 August 2009), [http://www.architectural-review.com/buildings/pavilion-by-lvaro-siza-and-rudolf-finsterwalder-insel-hombroich-foundation-ruhr-valley-germany/8600969.article Pavilion by \u00c1lvaro Siza and Rudolf Finsterwalder, Insel Hombroich Foundation, Ruhr Valley, Germany] ''The Architectural Review''.</ref> Most recently, he started coordinating the rehabilitation of the monuments and architectonic heritage of [[Cidade Velha]] (Old Village) in Santiago, an island of Cape Verde.\n\nCommissioned after winning an international competition in 2010, Siza and Granada-based Juan Domingo Santos unveiled designs for a new entrance and visitors center at the [[Alhambra]] in 2014.<ref>Karissa Rosenfield (11 March 2014), [http://www.archdaily.com/485230/alvaro-siza-juan-domingo-santos-design-new-gate-of-alhambra/ \u00c1lvaro Siza + Juan Domingo Santos Design \"New Gate of Alhambra\"] ''ArchDaily''.</ref>\n\nBy 2012, Siza warned that he might close his Portuguese office because of a lack of contracts.<ref>Raphael Minder (9 November 2012), [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/10/arts/10iht-scportugal10.html Celebrating a Year of Culture Amid Hard Times in Portugal] ''[[International Herald Tribune]]''.</ref> In 2019, he was commissioned with his first project in the United States, a 450-foot-tall, 37-story apartment building at [[56th Street (Manhattan)|611 West 56th Street]] in [[Manhattan]].<ref>Tim McKeough (30 August 2019), [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/30/realestate/another-starchitect-arrives-in-new-york.html Another Starchitect Arrives in New York] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\n===Teaching===\nSiza taught at FAUP from 1966 to 1969, returning in 1976. In addition to his teaching there, he has been a visiting professor at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Design|Graduate School of Design, Harvard University]]; the [[University of Pennsylvania]]; Los Andes University of Bogota; and the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne]].<ref name=\"Pritzker\">[http://www.pritzkerprize.com/laureates/1992/bio.html Pritzker Architecture Prize: Alvaro Siza Vieira] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222001519/http://pritzkerprize.com/laureates/1992/bio.html |date=22 December 2010 }}, retrieved 1 May 2011.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn July 2014 Siza announced his decision to donate the large part of his architectural archive to the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] (CCA) in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]],  Canada, in order to make his materials \"accessible alongside the work of other modern and contemporary architects\",<ref>Siza, \u00c1lvaro (23 July 2014), [https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search/details/collection/object/447183 \"\u00c1lvaro Siza's fonds\"], ''[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] (CCA)''.</ref> while also giving specific project archives to the [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Gulbenkian]] in [[Lisbon]] and [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o de Serralves]] in [[Porto]], [[Portugal]].<ref>{{cite news |first= Lu\u00eds Miguel |last= Qeuir\u00f3s |date= 9 July 2015 |url=http://www.publico.pt/culturaipsilon/noticia/alvaro-siza-doa-40-projectos-a-serralves-1701463 |title=\u00c1lvaro Siza doa 40 projectos a Serralves |newspaper= [[P\u00fablico (Portugal)]]}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n[[File:Escola Superior de Educa\u00e7\u00e3o de Set\u00fabal Photo by Christian G\u00e4nshirt.JPG|thumb|Library of the Escola Superior de Educa\u00e7\u00e3o de Set\u00fabal, 1986-1994]] \nIn 1987, the dean of [[Harvard Graduate School of Design]], the Spanish architect [[Jos\u00e9 Rafael Moneo|Rafael Moneo]], organized the first show of Siza's work in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |first= Nicholas |last= Ouroussoff |date= 5 August 2007 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/05/arts/design/05ouro.html |title= Modernist Master's Deceptively Simple World |newspaper= [[New York Times]]}}</ref> In 1992, he was awarded with the renowned [[Pritzker Prize]] for the renovation project that he coordinated in the [[Chiado]] area of Lisbon, a historic commercial sector that was all but completely destroyed by fire in August 1988.<ref name=\"Pritzker\"/>\n\nOther prizes include: The Golden Medal of The Superior Council of Architecture of the College of Architects of Madrid in 1988; [[Mies van der Rohe Award for European Architecture]], the Prince of Wales Prize in Urban Design from [[Harvard University]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gsd.harvard.edu/academic/fellowships/prizes/green_prize.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=8 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210065635/http://www.gsd.harvard.edu/academic/fellowships/prizes/green_prize.htm |archive-date=10 December 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the [[Alvar Aalto Medal]] in 1988; Portugal's National Prize of Architecture 1993; the Arnold W. Brunner Memorial Prize by the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]] and the [[Praemium Imperiale]] in 1998, the [[Wolf Prize in Arts]] in 2001, the Urbanism Special Grand Prize of France 2005.\n\nSiza's [[Iber\u00ea Camargo Foundation]] in Porto Alegre, his first project built in Brazilian territory, was honoured by the [[Venice Architecture Biennale]] with the Golden Lion award in 2002.<ref>[http://labiennale.org/en/architecture/history/8.html?back=true 8th International Architecture Exhibition 2002] La Biennale di Venezia.</ref> In 2007 the Brazilian Government awarded him the Cultural Merit Order Medal. More recently he was awarded the [[Royal Institute of British Architects|RIBA]]'s 2009 [[Royal Gold Medal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architecture.com/Awards/RoyalGoldMedal/RoyalGoldMedal2009/RoyalGoldMedal2009.aspx|title=Royal Gold Medal 2009|publisher=[[Royal Institute of British Architects]]|website=architecture.com|accessdate=19 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140605102840/http://www.architecture.com/Awards/RoyalGoldMedal/RoyalGoldMedal2009/RoyalGoldMedal2009.aspx|archive-date=5 June 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the [[International Union of Architects]]' 2011 [[International Union of Architects#UIA Gold Medal|Gold Medal]].<ref>{{cite news | title =2011 UIA Gold Medal | publisher =UIA | date =18 April 2011 | url =http://www.uia-architectes.org/texte/england/PRIZE/UIA2011/2uia2011.html | accessdate =28 September 2011 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20110920021359/http://www.uia-architectes.org/texte/england/PRIZE/UIA2011/2uia2011.html | archive-date =20 September 2011 | url-status =dead | df =dmy-all }}</ref> Siza was awarded by the [[Venice Architecture Biennale]] (13th Edition) with the Golden Lion for lifetime achievement (2012).\n\nSiza was conferred the title of Honoris Causa Doctor by the following universities: [[Polytechnic University of Valencia]]; [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne]]; [[University of Palermo]]; University Menendez Pelayo, in Santander; Universidad Nacional de Ingenier\u00eda in Lima, Peru; University of Coimbra; [[Lus\u00edada University of Porto]]; Universidade Federal de Para\u00edba; the Universit\u00e0 degli Studi di Napoli Federico II, Polo delle Scienze e delle Tecnologie, in Naples; the University of Architecture and Urbanism of Bucharest \"Ion Mincu\", Romania (2005); and the [[University of Pavia]], Italy (2007). He is a member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] as well as Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]], the [[American Institute of Architects]], the ''Acad\u00e9mie d'Architecture de France'' and the [[European Academy of Sciences and Arts]].\n\n==Civil awards and decorations==\n* [[File:PRT Order of Saint James of the Sword - Grand Officer BAR.png|80px]] Grand Officer of the [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword]], [[Portugal]] (6 June 1992)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\">{{cite web|title=Cidad\u00e3os Nacionais Agraciados com Ordens Portuguesas|url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=153|website=P\u00e1gina Oficial das Ordens Honor\u00edficas Portuguesas|accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:PRT Order of Prince Henry - Grand Cross BAR.png|80px]] Grand-Cross of the [[Order of Prince Henry]], [[Portugal]] (9 July 1999)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\"/>\n* [[File:POR Ordem da Instrucao Publica Gra-Cruz BAR.svg|80px]] Grand-Cross of the [[Order of Public Instruction (Portugal)|Order of Public Instruction]], Portugal (6 April 2017)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\"/>\n\n==Selected projects==\n[[File:Swimmingpool on the Beach at Le\u00e7a da Palmeira by Christian G\u00e4nshirt.JPG|thumb|[[Piscinas de Mar\u00e9s]] at [[Le\u00e7a da Palmeira]]]]\n[[File:Igreja marco canaveses.JPG|thumb|Marco de Canavezes Church]]\n[[File:Pavilion of the Portugal at the 1998 Lisbon World Exposition.JPG|thumb|[[Expo'98]] pavilion of Portugal with its concrete veil]]\n[[File:FundacaoIbereCamargo.JPG|thumb|Ibere Camargo Foundation]]\n{{Main|List of works by  \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira}}\nWorks by Siza include the [[Iber\u00ea Camargo Foundation]], the [[Serralves]] museum, and the [[New Orleans (Rotterdam)|New Orleans building]].\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* 2012, January: ''Alturas de Machu Picchu: Mart\u00edn Chambi - \u00c1lvaro Siza at Work'', at [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], [[Montreal]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/events/3200/alturas-de-machu-picchu-martin-chambi-alvaro-siza-at-work |title= Alturas de Machu Picchu: Mart\u00edn Chambi \u2013 \u00c1lvaro Siza at work |work= [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] |date= 26 January 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 2014, March: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[Aedes Architecture Forum]], [[Berlin]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch.<ref>''The Pearl of Granada remains untouched'' in the [[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|FAZ]]. 5 May 2014. Page 14</ref>\n* 2014, June: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[Vitra (furniture)|Vitra Campus]], [[Weil am Rhein]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch. - Opening of [[Art Basel]] and the \u00c1lvaro-Siza-Promenade<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.design-museum.de/en/exhibitions/detailseiten/siza.html |title= The Alhambra Project |work= [[Vitra Design Museum]] |date= 13 June 2014}}</ref>\n* 2015, February: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[Palace of Charles V]], [[Granada]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.alhambra-patronato.es/index.php?id=746 |title= Visiones de la Alhambra |work= [[Council of the Alhambra and Generalife]] |date= 9 February 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015, May: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[National Museum of Art, Architecture and Design]], [[Oslo]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch. - Official Visit of the [[President of Portugal]] to [[Norway]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://nasjonalmuseet.no/no/utstillinger_og_aktiviteter/utstillinger/nasjonalmuseet__arkitektur/%C3%81lvaro+Siza+Vieira.+Visions+of+the+Alhambra.b7C_wlzYWY.ips |title= \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira. Visions of the Alhambra |work= [[National Museum of Art, Architecture and Design]] |date= 4 May 2015}}</ref>\n* 2016, July: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[Aga Khan Museum]], [[Toronto]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.agakhanmuseum.org/exhibitions/alvaro-siza-gateway-alhambra |title= \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira. Gateway to the Alhambra |work= [[Aga Khan Museum]] |date= 23 July 2016}}</ref>\n* 2017, March: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[Serralves]] Museum, [[Porto]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://visao.sapo.pt/actualidade/visaose7e/ver/2017-03-08-Visoes-da-Alhambra-Serralves-mostra-o-projeto-de-Siza-Vieira-para-Granada |title= Visions of the Alhambra showcases \u00c1lvaro Siza's project for Granada |work= [[Serralves]] |date= 8 March 2017}}</ref>\n* 2017, June: ''Architecture on Canvas'', at the [[Nadir Afonso Contemporary Art Museum]] , [[Chaves (Portugal)|Chaves]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://diarioatual.com/chaves-arquitetura-tela-nova-exposicao-nadir-afonso-no-macna/ |title= Architecture on Canvas is MACNA's new exhibition |work= [[Nadir Afonso Contemporary Art Museum]] |date= 11 July 2017}}</ref>\n* 2018, May: ''AlfaroSiza'', no [[ESPAI ALFARO]], [[Valencia]]. Curators: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch. & Fran Silvestre, Arch.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://aasarchitecture.com/2018/05/alfaro-siza-exhibition.html |title= Dialogues between \u00c1lvaro Siza and Andreu Alfaro |work= [[ESPAI ALFARO]] |date= 30 May 2018}}</ref>\n* 2019, February: ''SIZA \u2013 Unseen & Unknown'', at the [[Museum for Architectural Drawing]], [[Berlin]]. Curators: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch. & [[Kristin Feireiss]] Dr.h.c. - [[Bauhaus]] Centennial<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tchoban-foundation.de/10-1-Exhibitions.html |title= SIZA \u2013 Unseen & Unknown |work= [[Museum for Architectural Drawing]] |date= 20 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Jacinto Rodrigues: ''\u00c1lvaro Siza / obra e m\u00e9todo'', Livraria Civiliza\u00e7\u00e3o Editora 1992, {{ISBN|972-26-1099-6}}\n* Peter Testa: ''\u00c1lvaro Siza'', Birkh\u00e4user 1996, {{ISBN|3-7643-5598-0}}\n* \u00c1lvaro Siza: ''City Sketches'', Birkh\u00e4user 1994, {{ISBN|3-7643-2820-7}}\n* Jorge Figueira (Hrsg.): ''\u00c1lvaro Siza. Modern Redux'' (Text: Alexandre Alves Costa, Jorge Figueira, Hans Ibelings, Guilherme Wisnik). Ostfildern: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2008, {{ISBN|978-3-7757-2298-8}} (English/German) und {{ISBN|978-3-7757-2276-6}} (English/Portuguese) \u2013 Projects 1998\u20132008\n* Raul Betti e Greta Ruffino, ''\u00c1lvaro Siza, Viagem sem Programa,'' Red Publishing 2012, {{ISBN|978-88-88492-22-3}} \n* Duarte, J.P. (2001) \"Customizing Mass Housing: a discursive grammar for Siza's houses at Malagueira\", PhD Dissertation, Massachusetts Institute of Technology\n* [[Kenneth Frampton]]: ''\u00c1lvaro Siza. Complete Works'', Phaidon, London, 2000, {{ISBN|978-0714840048}}\n* [[Philip Jodidio]]: \u00c1lvaro Siza: Complete Works 1952-2013,Taschen 2013, {{ISBN|978-3836521710}}\n* Jo\u00e3o Carmo Sim\u00f5es, J. Figueira, P. Tunhas: [https://www.monadebooks.com/books/m2 ''\u00c1lvaro Siza / Museu Nadir Afonso'']{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Lisboa: '''monade''', 2016, {{ISBN|978-989-99485-1-8}}\n[[File:Monade Museu Nadir Afonso.jpg|thumb|[https://www.monadebooks.com/books/m2 Museu Nadir Afonso] (2016)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{commons|\u00c1lvaro Siza}}\n\n{{Pritzker Prize laureates}}\n{{Wolf Prize in Arts}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sizaviera, Alvaro}}\n[[Category:Portuguese architects]]\n[[Category:Architecture educators]]\n[[Category:Architecture writers]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:\u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira buildings| 01]]\n[[Category:Pritzker Architecture Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Wolf Prize in Arts laureates]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Academy of Sciences and Arts]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Praemium Imperiale]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Gold Medal]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Matosinhos]]\n[[Category:University of Porto alumni]]\n[[Category:Modernist architects]]\n[[Category:Postmodern architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century Portuguese architects]]\n[[Category:21st-century architects]]\n[[Category:21st-century Portuguese people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira\n| image                 = Siza Vieira na Exponor.JPG\n| caption               = \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira in 2012\n| birth_name            = \u00c1lvaro Joaquim de Melo Siza Vieira\n| birth_date            = {{birth-date and age|25 June 1933}}\n| birth_place           = [[Matosinhos]], Portugal\n| death_date            =\n| death_place           =\n| nationality           = Portuguese\n| alma_mater            = [[University of Porto]]\n| awards                = [[Pritzker Prize]] (1992), [[Royal Gold Medal]] (2009), [[International Union of Architects#UIA Gold Medal|UIA Gold Medal]] (2011), Golden Lion for lifetime achievement (2012)\n| significant_buildings = [[Porto School of Architecture|Faculty of Architecture, Porto]]\n| significant_projects  =\n| significant_design    =\n}}\n[[File:Berlin schlesische-str-7 bonjour-tristesse 20050224 p1010029.jpg|thumb|\"[[Bonjour Tristesse (building)|Bonjour Tristesse]]\" apartments, Schlesische Stra\u00dfe, Berlin]]\n\n'''\u00c1lvaro Joaquim de Melo Siza Vieira''', {{small|[[Order of St. James of the Sword|GOSE]], [[Order of Infante D. Henrique|GCIH]], [[Order of Public Instruction (Portugal)|GCIP]]}} (born 25 June 1933), is a Portuguese [[architect]], and [[architectural educator]]. He is internationally known as '''\u00c1lvaro Siza''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8a\u026bv\u0250\u027eu \u02c8siz\u0250}}) and in Portugal as '''Siza Vieira''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8siz\u0250 \u02c8vjej\u027e\u0250}}).\n\n==Early life and education==\nSiza was born in [[Matosinhos]], a small coastal town near [[Porto]].  He graduated in architecture in 1955, at the former School of Fine Arts of the [[University of Porto]], the current [[Porto School of Architecture|FAUP]] &ndash; ''Faculdade de Arquitectura da Universidade do Porto''. \n\n==Career==\nSiza completed his first built work (four houses in Matosinhos) even before ending his studies in 1954, the same year that he first opened his private practice in Porto. Along with [[Fernando T\u00e1vora]], he soon became one of the references of the [[Porto School of Architecture]] where both were teachers. Both architects worked together between 1955 and 1958. Another architect he has collaborated with is [[Eduardo Souto de Moura]], e.g. on Portugal's [[Pavilion of Portugal in Expo'98|flagship pavilions]] at [[Expo '98]] in Lisbon and [[Expo 2000]] in Hannover, as well as on the [[Serpentine Gallery|Serpentine Pavillon]] 2005. Siza's work is often described as \"poetic [[modernism]]\";<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/oct/08/alvaro.siza.riba.prize Jonathan Glancey: ''A Gold Medal for Siza? About time''] in ''The Guardian'', 8 October 2008</ref> he himself has contributed to publications on [[Luis Barrag\u00e1n]].\n\nAmong Siza's earliest works to gain public attention was a public pool complex (named [[Piscinas de Mar\u00e9s]]) he created in the 1960s for Le\u00e7a da Palmeira, a fishing town and summer resort north of Porto. Completed in 1966, both of the two swimming pools (one for children, the other for adults) as well as the building with changing rooms and a cafe are set into the natural rock formation on the site with unobstructed views of the sea.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/27/arts/a-portuguese-wins-pritzker-award.html |title= A Portuguese Wins Pritzker Award |newspaper= [[New York Times]] |date= 27 April 1992}}</ref> In 1977, following the revolution in Portugal, the city government of [[\u00c9vora]] commissioned Siza to plan a housing project in the rural outskirts of the town. It was to be one of several that he would do for SAAL (''Servi\u00e7o de Apoio Ambulat\u00f3rio Local''), the national housing association, consisting of 1,200 low-cost, housing units, some one-story and some two-story row houses, all with courtyards.<ref name=\"Pritzker\"/> He was also a member of the team which reconstructed Chiado, the historic center of Lisbon destroyed by a fire in 1988.\n\nMost of his best known works are located in his hometown Porto: the Boa Nova Tea House (1963), the [[FAUP|Faculty of Architecture]] (1987\u201393), and the [[Serralves Foundation|Serralves Museum of Contemporary Art]] (1997). Since the mid-1970s, Siza has been involved in numerous designs for public housing, public pools,<ref>Patrick Lynch (23 October 2008), [http://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/critics/lvaro-siza-swimming-pools-with-depth/1904917.article \u00c1lvaro Siza: swimming pools with depth] ''The Architect's Journal.''</ref> and universities. Between 1995 and 2009, Siza has been working on an architecture museum on [[Museum Insel Hombroich|Hombroich island]], completed in collaboration with Rudolf Finsterwalder.<ref>Kieran Long (1 August 2009), [http://www.architectural-review.com/buildings/pavilion-by-lvaro-siza-and-rudolf-finsterwalder-insel-hombroich-foundation-ruhr-valley-germany/8600969.article Pavilion by \u00c1lvaro Siza and Rudolf Finsterwalder, Insel Hombroich Foundation, Ruhr Valley, Germany] ''The Architectural Review''.</ref> Most recently, he started coordinating the rehabilitation of the monuments and architectonic heritage of [[Cidade Velha]] (Old Village) in Santiago, an island of Cape Verde.\n\nCommissioned after winning an international competition in 2010, Siza and Granada-based Juan Domingo Santos unveiled designs for a new entrance and visitors center at the [[Alhambra]] in 2014.<ref>Karissa Rosenfield (11 March 2014), [http://www.archdaily.com/485230/alvaro-siza-juan-domingo-santos-design-new-gate-of-alhambra/ \u00c1lvaro Siza + Juan Domingo Santos Design \"New Gate of Alhambra\"] ''ArchDaily''.</ref>\n\nBy 2012, Siza warned that he might close his Portuguese office because of a lack of contracts.<ref>Raphael Minder (9 November 2012), [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/10/arts/10iht-scportugal10.html Celebrating a Year of Culture Amid Hard Times in Portugal] ''[[International Herald Tribune]]''.</ref> In 2019, he was commissioned with his first project in the United States, a 450-foot-tall, 37-story apartment building at [[56th Street (Manhattan)|611 West 56th Street]] in [[Manhattan]].<ref>Tim McKeough (30 August 2019), [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/30/realestate/another-starchitect-arrives-in-new-york.html Another Starchitect Arrives in New York] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\n===Teaching===\nSiza taught at FAUP from 1966 to 1969, returning in 1976. In addition to his teaching there, he has been a visiting professor at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Design|Graduate School of Design, Harvard University]]; the [[University of Pennsylvania]]; Los Andes University of Bogota; and the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne]].<ref name=\"Pritzker\">[http://www.pritzkerprize.com/laureates/1992/bio.html Pritzker Architecture Prize: Alvaro Siza Vieira] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222001519/http://pritzkerprize.com/laureates/1992/bio.html |date=22 December 2010 }}, retrieved 1 May 2011.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn July 2014 Siza announced his decision to donate the large part of his architectural archive to the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] (CCA) in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]],  Canada, in order to make his materials \"accessible alongside the work of other modern and contemporary architects\",<ref>Siza, \u00c1lvaro (23 July 2014), [https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search/details/collection/object/447183 \"\u00c1lvaro Siza's fonds\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] (CCA)''.</ref> while also giving specific project archives to the [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Gulbenkian]] in [[Lisbon]] and [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o de Serralves]] in [[Porto]], [[Portugal]].<ref>{{cite news |first= Lu\u00eds Miguel |last= Qeuir\u00f3s |date= 9 July 2015 |url=http://www.publico.pt/culturaipsilon/noticia/alvaro-siza-doa-40-projectos-a-serralves-1701463 |title=\u00c1lvaro Siza doa 40 projectos a Serralves |newspaper= [[P\u00fablico (Portugal)]]}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n[[File:Escola Superior de Educa\u00e7\u00e3o de Set\u00fabal Photo by Christian G\u00e4nshirt.JPG|thumb|Library of the Escola Superior de Educa\u00e7\u00e3o de Set\u00fabal, 1986-1994]] \nIn 1987, the dean of [[Harvard Graduate School of Design]], the Spanish architect [[Jos\u00e9 Rafael Moneo|Rafael Moneo]], organized the first show of Siza's work in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |first= Nicholas |last= Ouroussoff |date= 5 August 2007 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/05/arts/design/05ouro.html |title= Modernist Master's Deceptively Simple World |newspaper= [[New York Times]]}}</ref> In 1992, he was awarded with the renowned [[Pritzker Prize]] for the renovation project that he coordinated in the [[Chiado]] area of Lisbon, a historic commercial sector that was all but completely destroyed by fire in August 1988.<ref name=\"Pritzker\"/>\n\nOther prizes include: The Golden Medal of The Superior Council of Architecture of the College of Architects of Madrid in 1988; [[Mies van der Rohe Award for European Architecture]], the Prince of Wales Prize in Urban Design from [[Harvard University]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gsd.harvard.edu/academic/fellowships/prizes/green_prize.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=8 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210065635/http://www.gsd.harvard.edu/academic/fellowships/prizes/green_prize.htm |archive-date=10 December 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the [[Alvar Aalto Medal]] in 1988; Portugal's National Prize of Architecture 1993; the Arnold W. Brunner Memorial Prize by the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]] and the [[Praemium Imperiale]] in 1998, the [[Wolf Prize in Arts]] in 2001, the Urbanism Special Grand Prize of France 2005.\n\nSiza's [[Iber\u00ea Camargo Foundation]] in Porto Alegre, his first project built in Brazilian territory, was honoured by the [[Venice Architecture Biennale]] with the Golden Lion award in 2002.<ref>[http://labiennale.org/en/architecture/history/8.html?back=true 8th International Architecture Exhibition 2002] La Biennale di Venezia.</ref> In 2007 the Brazilian Government awarded him the Cultural Merit Order Medal. More recently he was awarded the [[Royal Institute of British Architects|RIBA]]'s 2009 [[Royal Gold Medal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architecture.com/Awards/RoyalGoldMedal/RoyalGoldMedal2009/RoyalGoldMedal2009.aspx|title=Royal Gold Medal 2009|publisher=[[Royal Institute of British Architects]]|website=architecture.com|accessdate=19 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140605102840/http://www.architecture.com/Awards/RoyalGoldMedal/RoyalGoldMedal2009/RoyalGoldMedal2009.aspx|archive-date=5 June 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the [[International Union of Architects]]' 2011 [[International Union of Architects#UIA Gold Medal|Gold Medal]].<ref>{{cite news | title =2011 UIA Gold Medal | publisher =UIA | date =18 April 2011 | url =http://www.uia-architectes.org/texte/england/PRIZE/UIA2011/2uia2011.html | accessdate =28 September 2011 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20110920021359/http://www.uia-architectes.org/texte/england/PRIZE/UIA2011/2uia2011.html | archive-date =20 September 2011 | url-status =dead | df =dmy-all }}</ref> Siza was awarded by the [[Venice Architecture Biennale]] (13th Edition) with the Golden Lion for lifetime achievement (2012).\n\nSiza was conferred the title of Honoris Causa Doctor by the following universities: [[Polytechnic University of Valencia]]; [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne]]; [[University of Palermo]]; University Menendez Pelayo, in Santander; Universidad Nacional de Ingenier\u00eda in Lima, Peru; University of Coimbra; [[Lus\u00edada University of Porto]]; Universidade Federal de Para\u00edba; the Universit\u00e0 degli Studi di Napoli Federico II, Polo delle Scienze e delle Tecnologie, in Naples; the University of Architecture and Urbanism of Bucharest \"Ion Mincu\", Romania (2005); and the [[University of Pavia]], Italy (2007). He is a member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] as well as Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]], the [[American Institute of Architects]], the ''Acad\u00e9mie d'Architecture de France'' and the [[European Academy of Sciences and Arts]].\n\n==Civil awards and decorations==\n* [[File:PRT Order of Saint James of the Sword - Grand Officer BAR.png|80px]] Grand Officer of the [[Military Order of Saint James of the Sword]], [[Portugal]] (6 June 1992)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\">{{cite web|title=Cidad\u00e3os Nacionais Agraciados com Ordens Portuguesas|url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=153|website=P\u00e1gina Oficial das Ordens Honor\u00edficas Portuguesas|accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:PRT Order of Prince Henry - Grand Cross BAR.png|80px]] Grand-Cross of the [[Order of Prince Henry]], [[Portugal]] (9 July 1999)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\"/>\n* [[File:POR Ordem da Instrucao Publica Gra-Cruz BAR.svg|80px]] Grand-Cross of the [[Order of Public Instruction (Portugal)|Order of Public Instruction]], Portugal (6 April 2017)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\"/>\n\n==Selected projects==\n[[File:Swimmingpool on the Beach at Le\u00e7a da Palmeira by Christian G\u00e4nshirt.JPG|thumb|[[Piscinas de Mar\u00e9s]] at [[Le\u00e7a da Palmeira]]]]\n[[File:Igreja marco canaveses.JPG|thumb|Marco de Canavezes Church]]\n[[File:Pavilion of the Portugal at the 1998 Lisbon World Exposition.JPG|thumb|[[Expo'98]] pavilion of Portugal with its concrete veil]]\n[[File:FundacaoIbereCamargo.JPG|thumb|Ibere Camargo Foundation]]\n{{Main|List of works by  \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira}}\nWorks by Siza include the [[Iber\u00ea Camargo Foundation]], the [[Serralves]] museum, and the [[New Orleans (Rotterdam)|New Orleans building]].\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* 2012, January: ''Alturas de Machu Picchu: Mart\u00edn Chambi - \u00c1lvaro Siza at Work'', at [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], [[Montreal]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/events/3200/alturas-de-machu-picchu-martin-chambi-alvaro-siza-at-work |title= Alturas de Machu Picchu: Mart\u00edn Chambi \u2013 \u00c1lvaro Siza at work |work= [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] |date= 26 January 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 2014, March: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[Aedes Architecture Forum]], [[Berlin]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch.<ref>''The Pearl of Granada remains untouched'' in the [[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|FAZ]]. 5 May 2014. Page 14</ref>\n* 2014, June: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[Vitra (furniture)|Vitra Campus]], [[Weil am Rhein]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch. - Opening of [[Art Basel]] and the \u00c1lvaro-Siza-Promenade<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.design-museum.de/en/exhibitions/detailseiten/siza.html |title= The Alhambra Project |work= [[Vitra Design Museum]] |date= 13 June 2014}}</ref>\n* 2015, February: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[Palace of Charles V]], [[Granada]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.alhambra-patronato.es/index.php?id=746 |title= Visiones de la Alhambra |work= [[Council of the Alhambra and Generalife]] |date= 9 February 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015, May: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[National Museum of Art, Architecture and Design]], [[Oslo]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch. - Official Visit of the [[President of Portugal]] to [[Norway]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://nasjonalmuseet.no/no/utstillinger_og_aktiviteter/utstillinger/nasjonalmuseet__arkitektur/%C3%81lvaro+Siza+Vieira.+Visions+of+the+Alhambra.b7C_wlzYWY.ips |title= \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira. Visions of the Alhambra |work= [[National Museum of Art, Architecture and Design]] |date= 4 May 2015}}</ref>\n* 2016, July: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[Aga Khan Museum]], [[Toronto]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.agakhanmuseum.org/exhibitions/alvaro-siza-gateway-alhambra |title= \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira. Gateway to the Alhambra |work= [[Aga Khan Museum]] |date= 23 July 2016}}</ref>\n* 2017, March: ''Visions of the Alhambra'', at the [[Serralves]] Museum, [[Porto]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://visao.sapo.pt/actualidade/visaose7e/ver/2017-03-08-Visoes-da-Alhambra-Serralves-mostra-o-projeto-de-Siza-Vieira-para-Granada |title= Visions of the Alhambra showcases \u00c1lvaro Siza's project for Granada |work= [[Serralves]] |date= 8 March 2017}}</ref>\n* 2017, June: ''Architecture on Canvas'', at the [[Nadir Afonso Contemporary Art Museum]] , [[Chaves (Portugal)|Chaves]]. Curator: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://diarioatual.com/chaves-arquitetura-tela-nova-exposicao-nadir-afonso-no-macna/ |title= Architecture on Canvas is MACNA's new exhibition |work= [[Nadir Afonso Contemporary Art Museum]] |date= 11 July 2017}}</ref>\n* 2018, May: ''AlfaroSiza'', no [[ESPAI ALFARO]], [[Valencia]]. Curators: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch. & Fran Silvestre, Arch.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://aasarchitecture.com/2018/05/alfaro-siza-exhibition.html |title= Dialogues between \u00c1lvaro Siza and Andreu Alfaro |work= [[ESPAI ALFARO]] |date= 30 May 2018}}</ref>\n* 2019, February: ''SIZA \u2013 Unseen & Unknown'', at the [[Museum for Architectural Drawing]], [[Berlin]]. Curators: Ant\u00f3nio Choupina, Arch. & [[Kristin Feireiss]] Dr.h.c. - [[Bauhaus]] Centennial<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tchoban-foundation.de/10-1-Exhibitions.html |title= SIZA \u2013 Unseen & Unknown |work= [[Museum for Architectural Drawing]] |date= 20 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Jacinto Rodrigues: ''\u00c1lvaro Siza / obra e m\u00e9todo'', Livraria Civiliza\u00e7\u00e3o Editora 1992, {{ISBN|972-26-1099-6}}\n* Peter Testa: ''\u00c1lvaro Siza'', Birkh\u00e4user 1996, {{ISBN|3-7643-5598-0}}\n* \u00c1lvaro Siza: ''City Sketches'', Birkh\u00e4user 1994, {{ISBN|3-7643-2820-7}}\n* Jorge Figueira (Hrsg.): ''\u00c1lvaro Siza. Modern Redux'' (Text: Alexandre Alves Costa, Jorge Figueira, Hans Ibelings, Guilherme Wisnik). Ostfildern: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2008, {{ISBN|978-3-7757-2298-8}} (English/German) und {{ISBN|978-3-7757-2276-6}} (English/Portuguese) \u2013 Projects 1998\u20132008\n* Raul Betti e Greta Ruffino, ''\u00c1lvaro Siza, Viagem sem Programa,'' Red Publishing 2012, {{ISBN|978-88-88492-22-3}} \n* Duarte, J.P. (2001) \"Customizing Mass Housing: a discursive grammar for Siza's houses at Malagueira\", PhD Dissertation, Massachusetts Institute of Technology\n* [[Kenneth Frampton]]: ''\u00c1lvaro Siza. Complete Works'', Phaidon, London, 2000, {{ISBN|978-0714840048}}\n* [[Philip Jodidio]]: \u00c1lvaro Siza: Complete Works 1952-2013,Taschen 2013, {{ISBN|978-3836521710}}\n* Jo\u00e3o Carmo Sim\u00f5es, J. Figueira, P. Tunhas: [https://www.monadebooks.com/books/m2 ''\u00c1lvaro Siza / Museu Nadir Afonso'']{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Lisboa: '''monade''', 2016, {{ISBN|978-989-99485-1-8}}\n[[File:Monade Museu Nadir Afonso.jpg|thumb|[https://www.monadebooks.com/books/m2 Museu Nadir Afonso] (2016)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{commons|\u00c1lvaro Siza}}\n\n{{Pritzker Prize laureates}}\n{{Wolf Prize in Arts}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sizaviera, Alvaro}}\n[[Category:Portuguese architects]]\n[[Category:Architecture educators]]\n[[Category:Architecture writers]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:\u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira buildings| 01]]\n[[Category:Pritzker Architecture Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Wolf Prize in Arts laureates]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Academy of Sciences and Arts]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Praemium Imperiale]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Gold Medal]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Matosinhos]]\n[[Category:University of Porto alumni]]\n[[Category:Modernist architects]]\n[[Category:Postmodern architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century Portuguese architects]]\n[[Category:21st-century architects]]\n[[Category:21st-century Portuguese people]]\n", "name_user": "Sadebag", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy:removed dead link mention", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%81lvaro_Siza_Vieira"}
{"title_page": "Ada Osakwe", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Ada Osakwe YGL.jpg\n| name   = Ada Osakwe\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = in 2018\n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1980}}\n| birth_place = [[Nigeria]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater         =[[University of Hull]]<br/> [[University of Warwick]]<br/>[[Kellogg School of Management]]\n| occupation                = Business executive\n| years_active              = 1990 \u2013 present\n| nationality               = Nigerian\n| known_for                 = \n| networth                  = \n| home_town                 = \n| title                     = [[Managing Director]] & [[CEO]], '''Agrolay Ventures'''\n|spouse                     = \n|term                       = \n|predecessor                = \n}}\n\n'''Ada Osakwe''' is a [[Nigeria]]n [[economist]], an [[entrepreneur]] and [[corporate executive]], who is the founder and [[chief executive officer]] of Agrolay Ventures, an agribusiness investment company based in [[Nigeria]], which invests in African agricultural food-related companies.<ref name=\"One\">{{cite web | url=https://www.afdb.org/en/annual-meetings-2016/speakers/ada-osakwe/ | title=African Development Bank Group: Annual Meetings, Lusaka: May 23 - 27, 2016: Speakers: Ada Osakwe, Chief Executive, Agrolay Ventures | date=23 May 2016 | accessdate=1 November 2017 | publisher=[[African Development Bank]] (AfDB) | author=AfDB | location=Abidjan | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107010428/https://www.afdb.org/en/annual-meetings-2016/speakers/ada-osakwe/ | archive-date=7 November 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref> From November 2012 until May 2015, Osakwe was the Senior Investment Adviser to Nigeria's Minister of Agriculture and Rural Development, [[Akinwumi Adesina]].<ref name=\"One\"/>\n\n==Background and education==\nOsakwe was born in Nigeria on 2 September 1981.<ref name=\"In\">{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mfonobongnsehe/2014/12/04/the-20-youngest-power-women-in-africa-2014/#26701c7830b0 |title=The 20 Youngest Power Women In Africa 2014 | date=4 December 2014 | accessdate=26 November 2017 | publisher=[[Forbes.com]] | first=Mfonobong | last=Nsehe}}</ref> She attended secondary school in [[Lagos]] for her A-Level education,<ref name=\"Det\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bellanaija.com/2013/05/move-back-to-nigeria-ada-osakwe-takes-the-leap-from-private-equity-fund-investor-to-special-investment-advisor-to-the-nigerian-minister-of-agriculture/ | title=Move Back to Nigeria: Ada Osakwe Takes the Leap from Private Equity Fund Investor to Special Investment Advisor to the Nigerian Minister of Agriculture | date=31 May 2013 | accessdate=1 November 2017 |publisher=Bellanaija.com| last=MoveBackToNigeria}}</ref> and graduated from the [[University of Hull]], in the United Kingdom, with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[Economics]]. Her [[Master of Science]] in Economics and Finance was obtained from the [[University of Warwick]], also in the UK. She also holds a [[Master of Business Administration]], obtained from the [[Kellogg School of Management]], at [[Northwestern University]], in [[Evanston, Illinois]] in the United States.<ref name=\"Det\"/><ref name=\"Two\">{{cite| url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2016/04/ada-osakwe-creative-food-entrepreneur/ | title=Ada Osakwe: The Creative Food Entrepreneur |location=Lagos |accessdate=1 November 2017 |date=4 April 2016 |first=Jemi |last=Ekunkunbor|newspaper=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nOsakwe first worked as an [[investment banker]] with [[BNP Paribas]] at their [[London]] office. She then worked as a Senior Investment Officer at the [[African Development Bank]] (AfDB), mainly in the area of infrastructure finance, serving in that capacity for four years. She was based in [[Tunis]]. Later, she served as Vice-President at Kuramo Capital Management, a [[private equity]] company based in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"One\" /><ref name=\"Three\">{{cite web|author=One Acre Fund | url=https://oneacrefund.org/about-us/board-and-advisors/governing-board/ada-osakwe/ |title=One Acre Fund: Governing Board: Ada Osakwe, Founder and Chief Executive, Agrolay Ventures | publisher=[[One Acre Fund]] |location=Kakamega |accessdate=1 November 2017 |date=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter her work with the Nigerian Ministry of Agriculture, Osakwe founded Agrolay Ventures. She also founded Nuli Juice, a restaurant chain in Nigeria.<ref name=\"Three\" /> In 2017, she was appointed to the board of [[One Acre Fund]], a Kenya-based financial and educational [[non-government organisation]] that serves small-scale farmers in [[Burundi]], [[Kenya]], [[Malawi]], [[Rwanda]], [[Tanzania]] and [[Uganda]].<ref name=\"Three\" />\n\n==Awards==\nIn December 2014, Osakwe was named among the \"Twenty Youngest Power Women in Africa 2014\", by [[Forbes Magazine]].<ref name=\"In\">{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mfonobongnsehe/2014/12/04/the-20-youngest-power-women-in-africa-2014/#26701c7830b0 |title=The 20 Youngest Power Women In Africa 2014 | date=4 December 2014 | accessdate=26 November 2017 | publisher=[[Forbes.com]] | first=Mfonobong | last=Nsehe}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Agriculture in Nigeria]]\n*[[Amira Elmissiry]]\n*[[Adiat Disu]]\n*[[Amy Jadesimi]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.agrolay.com/ Website of Agrolay Ventures]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osakwe, Ada}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nigerian economists]]\n[[Category:Nigerian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Hull]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Warwick]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Kellogg School of Management alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Lagos]]\n[[Category:Nigerian women in business]]\n[[Category:Nigerian women business executives]]\n[[Category:Nigerian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Nigerian food company founders]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriates in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Ada Osakwe YGL.jpg\n| name   = Ada Osakwe\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = in 2018\n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1980}}\n| birth_place = [[Nigeria]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater         =[[University of Hull]]<br/> [[University of Warwick]]<br/>[[Kellogg School of Management]]\n| occupation                = Business executive\n| years_active              = 1990 \u2013 present\n| nationality               = Nigerian\n| known_for                 = \n| networth                  = \n| home_town                 = \n| title                     = [[Managing Director]] & [[CEO]], '''Agrolay Ventures'''\n|spouse                     = \n|term                       = \n|predecessor                = \n}}\n\n'''Ada Osakwe''' is a [[Nigeria]]n [[economist]], an [[entrepreneur]] and [[corporate executive]], who is the founder and [[chief executive officer]] of Agrolay Ventures, an agribusiness investment company based in [[Nigeria]], which invests in African agricultural food-related companies.<ref name=\"One\">{{cite web | url=https://www.afdb.org/en/annual-meetings-2016/speakers/ada-osakwe/ | title=African Development Bank Group: Annual Meetings, Lusaka: May 23 - 27, 2016: Speakers: Ada Osakwe, Chief Executive, Agrolay Ventures | date=23 May 2016 | accessdate=1 November 2017 | publisher=[[African Development Bank]] (AfDB) | author=AfDB | location=Abidjan | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107010428/https://www.afdb.org/en/annual-meetings-2016/speakers/ada-osakwe/ | archive-date=7 November 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref> From November 2012 until May 2015, Osakwe was the Senior Investment Adviser to Nigeria's Minister of Agriculture and Rural Development, [[Akinwumi Adesina]].<ref name=\"One\"/>\n\n==Background and education==\nOsakwe was born in Nigeria on 2 September 1981.<ref name=\"In\">{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mfonobongnsehe/2014/12/04/the-20-youngest-power-women-in-africa-2014/#26701c7830b0 |title=The 20 Youngest Power Women In Africa 2014 | date=4 December 2014 | accessdate=26 November 2017 | publisher=[[Forbes.com]] | first=Mfonobong | last=Nsehe}}</ref> She attended secondary school in [[Lagos]] for her A-Level education,<ref name=\"Det\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bellanaija.com/2013/05/move-back-to-nigeria-ada-osakwe-takes-the-leap-from-private-equity-fund-investor-to-special-investment-advisor-to-the-nigerian-minister-of-agriculture/ | title=Move Back to Nigeria: Ada Osakwe Takes the Leap from Private Equity Fund Investor to Special Investment Advisor to the Nigerian Minister of Agriculture | date=31 May 2013 | accessdate=1 November 2017 |publisher=Bellanaija.com| last=MoveBackToNigeria}}</ref> and graduated from the [[University of Hull]], in the United Kingdom, with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[Economics]]. Her [[Master of Science]] in Economics and Finance was obtained from the [[University of Warwick]], also in the UK. She also holds a [[Master of Business Administration]], obtained from the [[Kellogg School of Management]], at [[Northwestern University]], in [[Evanston, Illinois]] in the United States.<ref name=\"Det\"/><ref name=\"Two\">{{cite| url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2016/04/ada-osakwe-creative-food-entrepreneur/ | title=Ada Osakwe: The Creative Food Entrepreneur |location=Lagos |accessdate=1 November 2017 |date=4 April 2016 |first=Jemi |last=Ekunkunbor|newspaper=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nOsakwe first worked as an [[investment banker]] with [[BNP Paribas]] at their [[London]] office. She then worked as a Senior Investment Officer at the [[African Development Bank]] (AfDB), mainly in the area of infrastructure finance, serving in that capacity for four years. She was based in [[Tunis]]. Later, she served as Vice-President at Kuramo Capital Management, a [[private equity]] company based in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"One\" /><ref name=\"Three\">{{cite web|author=One Acre Fund | url=https://oneacrefund.org/about-us/board-and-advisors/governing-board/ada-osakwe/ |title=One Acre Fund: Governing Board: Ada Osakwe, Founder and Chief Executive, Agrolay Ventures | publisher=[[One Acre Fund]] |location=Kakamega |accessdate=1 November 2017 |date=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter her work with the Nigerian Ministry of Agriculture, Osakwe founded Agrolay Ventures. She also founded Nuli Juice, a restaurant chain in Nigeria.<ref name=\"Three\" /> In 2017, she was appointed to the board of [[One Acre Fund]], a Kenya-based financial and educational [[non-government organisation]] that serves small-scale farmers in [[Burundi]], [[Kenya]], [[Malawi]], [[Rwanda]], [[Tanzania]] and [[Uganda]].<ref name=\"Three\" />\n\n==Awards==\nIn December 2014, Osakwe was named among the \"Twenty Youngest Power Women in Africa 2014\", by [[Forbes Magazine]].<ref name=\"In\">{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mfonobongnsehe/2014/12/04/the-20-youngest-power-women-in-africa-2014/#26701c7830b0 |title=The 20 Youngest Power Women In Africa 2014 | date=4 December 2014 | accessdate=26 November 2017 | publisher=[[Forbes.com]] | first=Mfonobong | last=Nsehe}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Agriculture in Nigeria]]\n*[[Amira Elmissiry]]\n*[[Adiat Disu]]\n*[[Amy Jadesimi]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.agrolay.com/ Website of Agrolay Ventures]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osakwe, Ada}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nigerian economists]]\n[[Category:Nigerian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Hull]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Warwick]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Kellogg School of Management alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Lagos]]\n[[Category:Nigerian women in business]]\n[[Category:Nigerian women business executives]]\n[[Category:Nigerian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Nigerian food company founders]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriates in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ada_Osakwe"}
